<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Ruling Party Difficult to Return to Power: Study Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) --Return to power by the ruling
Awami League (AL) in the next general election might be difficult
if the party fails to resolve the current internal feud in the
grassroots level and choose candidates in some cases carefully,
leaders of a fact-finding team of AL predicted.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina had assigned former leaders of AL'
s student wing Bangladesh Chattra League (BCL) for fact-finding to
prepare a secret report on the party's position in all the 300
seats of the parliament, with the view to having a clear picture
on the prospects of her party in the next general election.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina wants to know her party position in the
grassroots level beforehand to fix correct strategy to win the
next election.
</P>
<P>
The leaders on completion of their fact-finding tour are now
preparing the report and will submit it to the prime minister and
AL Chief Sheikh Hasina soon. The student leaders in 18 groups
visited all the 64 districts for doing their job.
</P>
<P>
Some of the student leaders told Xinhua that unless AL settles
the infighting of the party leaders in the grassroots level and
drops some candidates, the party might lose 25 seats in the next
election. In some cases brawl was so serious that leaders of a
single chapter do not sit together.
</P>
<P>
They said that some of the cabinet members and a few sitting
lawmakers of the ruling party have made their position risky in
their constituencies for the next election through their actions.
</P>
<P>
The party will have to change candidates in these cases, the
student leaders said, declining to name the ministers and the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The leaders observed that the popularity of Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina went up in four years, but this would not be so much
helpful in winning the election unless the party resolves the
internal wrangles and choose candidates carefully.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that keeping the success and failure of the
government now aside, the party should immediately give attention
to settling the internal quarrels among the leaders in the
grassroots level.
</P>
<P>
Hasina took the decision a day after she met her cabinet
colleagues at a meeting in the capital where she said the next
election will be held some time in October next year and her
government will stay in power till July 13.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina took the decision to know the position of her
party in the backdrop of opposition's decision to form electoral
alliance in the next general election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
