<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visiting British Minister Stresses Free and Fair Election in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Free and fair election is a
must for continuity of democracy, visiting British Home Minister
Jack Straw said here Sunday, suggesting guarantee of a pre-
election environment wherein all sides can debate freely.
</P>
<P>
Democracy is the "only future" for Bangladesh, he told
reporters at a press briefing after ending his 24-hour visit to
Dhaka during which he met with opposition leader Begum Zia and
held official talks with his Bangladesh counterpart Home Minister
Mohammad Nasim.
</P>
<P>
"Economic situation of a country depends on how strengthened
are the democratic institutions and these two go hand in hand," he
told the newsmen at the press briefing.
</P>
<P>
His observations stemmed from his first-hand view of Bangladesh
's political scenario marked by strikes and hartals (destructive
strikes) amid opposition movement for resignation of the
government and immediate elections.
</P>
<P>
When referring to the immigrant issue, Straw said the British
government would do whatever possible to smoothen the visa
procedures at the Dhaka immigration office, which is one of the
busiest centers in the country, receiving a large number of
applications, of which 75 percent are approved.
</P>
<P>
At present there are 300,000 Britons of Bangladeshi origin, he
informed.
</P>
<P>
Issues like criminality, corruption, human rights and also
commercial relations were discussed during the official talks
between the two home ministers, Straw said.
</P>
<P>
As a prominent member of Tony Blair's cabinet and the topmost
representative of the current British government to visit
Bangladesh, Straw arrived in Dhaka Saturday evening and held
official talks Sunday with his Bangladeshi counterpart, Mohammad
Nasim. He also called on leader of the Opposition Begum Khaleda
Zia and Chief Justice Latifur Rahman.
</P>
</TEXT>
