<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian GP: Schumacher Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ferrari's Michael Schumacher won
the Italian Grand Prix in Monza on Sunday, moving to within two
points of his arch-rival, McLaren's Mika Hakkinen, at the top of
the championship standings.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher led all the way in a race marred by a violent crash
at the start, which left Ferrari team-mate Rubens Barrichello,
McLaren's David Coulthard and four other drivers out at the first
chicane.
</P>
<P>
After ten laps run behind the safety car, Schumacher's Ferrari
steadily pulled away from Hakkinen's McLaren, which appeared to
lack the advantage of speed it had in Belgium two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen finished second and Ralf Schumacher, Michael's brother,
took the third spot in a Williams.
</P>
<P>
It was Schumacher's third victory at Monza and Ferrari's
seventh this season, a record not achieved by the team since 1953.
</P>
<P>
The German, who has now equalled Brazilian Ayrton Senna's
record of 41 career victories, was so overcome that at the press
conference after the race he broke down in tears and was unable to
continue.
</P>
<P>
The victory was an important boost for team morale which had
suffered after a series of disappointing results culminating in
Hakkinen's overtaking of Schumacher in the last laps of the
Belgian Grand prix two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The Finn now leads the championship standings with 80 points to
Schumacher's 78. In the constructors standings McLaren leads
Ferrari by 131 points to 127.
</P>
<P>
With three races to go, the stage is set for a dramatic finish
to the Formula 1 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
