<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
on Monday discussed with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak the
latest developments of the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat paid a brief visit to Egypt in the day, during which he
held talks with Mubarak at Burg al Arab airport, to the west of the
Mediterranean port city of Alexandria. The meeting came one day
after the Palestinian Central Council (PCC) decided to delay
declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
Arafat briefed Mubarak on his meeting with U.S. President Bill
Clinton last Wednesday in New York and some ideas raised during the
meeting which were not accepted by Israel, Egyptian Information
Minister Safwat el-Sharif said after the talks.
</P>
<P>
El-Sharif did not specify the ideas. But reports have said that
Arafat has proposed "Islamic sovereignty" via the Jerusalem
Committee over the Islamic shrines in the holy city, an idea which
Israeli officials have said they totally reject.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also briefed Mubarak on the PCC's decision to postpone
statehood declaration and to reconvene by November 15 to consider
further steps in this regard, the Egyptian minister told reporters.
</P>
<P>
PCC's decision is intended to give a chance to the international
community, Israel and other concerned parties to seek a
breakthrough and reach a peace agreement between the Palestinians
and Israel, el-Sharif quoted Arafat as saying.
</P>
<P>
El-Sharif said the two leaders exchanged views on Clinton's
proposals on resuming the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations on the
issues discussed at the Camp David summit, which ended on July 25
without an agreement mainly due to disputes over the status of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks are expected to resume
within the coming few weeks with the U.S. participation, he added,
without giving a date.
</P>
<P>
Monday's visit is Arafat's eighth to Egypt since the collapse of
the Camp David summit. He has left for Oman after talks with
Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
