<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Agricultural engineers and farmers in the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) can now get information on farming, post their
queries and receive answers from experts, through a new service on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Internet service has been launched by the International
Center for Agricultural Research in the Dry Areas (ICARDA) Arab
Peninsula Regional Program's (APRP) regional office in Dubai, in
cooperation with the Central Lab for Agriculture in Egypt, the
official WAM news agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The service will not only offer information to agricultural
engineers but also solve their problems on the spot.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's export of marine products is to exceed 100
million U.S. dollars during the current Iranian calendar year
(started March 20), while the figure stood at 63 million dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
Caviar, one of Iran's major non-oil exports, will make up 50
percent of the total export value, Lotfollah Saidi, deputy chief of
Iran's Fisheries Organization, said.
</P>
<P>
Saidi said that some 155 million dollars have been allocated for
the purchase of nine fishing trawlers in a bid to raise the fishery
capacity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Some 14 new fishing ports are also under construction, five of
them will be completed and join the present 67 fishing ports by
March 2001.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Jeddah-based Islamic Corporation for
Development of the Private Sector (ICD) and the Bahrain-based Gulf
Finance House (GFH) have agreed to set up the Injazat Technology
Fund, the first of its kind to finance technology development in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The 50-million-U.S.-dollar fund will be jointly undertaken by
GFH and ICD, which will invest 12.5 million dollars each, and the
expected life of the fund is five years.
</P>
<P>
The Communications Development Corporation (CDC), a Dubai-based
company, will provide investment, banking and corporate advisory
services as a technical advisor to the Injazat Technology Fund.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be set up in Bahrain and will also operate from
the Dubai Internet City once the application formalities are
completed.
</P>
<P>
It will invest in small- and medium-sized technology companies
in the Gulf, the Middle East and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The number of mobile phone users in Egypt is expected
to soar to 5.74 million by 2003 from the current 1.4 million,
according to a study conducted by Egypt's leading communication
consultant Gertner Group International.
</P>
<P>
Egypt would thus step up to the third place after Turkey and
South Africa in terms of cellular phone subscriber number in the
Middle East and Africa region.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has reached
an agreement with Jordan on expanding bilateral trade ties.
</P>
<P>
The deal would help remove obstacles in bilateral trade and
speed up the establishment of a joint free trade zone by 2007, said
Jordanian attache at the Palestinian territories Adnan al-Azab.
</P>
<P>
The deal would facilitate bilateral trade movement and promote
marketing and competition levels of each country's products, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
