<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Report Accuses Entertainment Industry of Targeting Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. government report
Monday accused the movie, video game and music industries of
aggressively marketing restricted violent products to underage
youths.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was released by the Federal Trade Commission
(FTC), said that such violent movies and video games are routinely
targeted toward younger people.
</P>
<P>
The report said materials submitted by the industry itself
showed intentional plans to promote their products to underage
audiences.
</P>
<P>
"The younger the audience, the more likely they are to be
influenced by TV advertising," one document from the entertainment
industry said.
</P>
<P>
The report was made under instructions of President Bill
Clinton and Congress after a deadly campus shooting incident in
which two students killed a teacher and 12 students before taking
their own lives in April last year.
</P>
<P>
"Target marketing to children of entertainment products with
violent content is pervasive and aggressive," FTC chairman Robert
Pitofsky said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The report found that of 44 movies rated R, which means only
for adults, 80 percent were marketed to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
And of 55 music recordings with "explicit" content labels, all
of them were marketed to children under 17, the report said. Of
118 electronic games with a "mature" rating for violence, 70
percent were targeted to children under 17.
</P>
<P>
The FTC report charged that Hollywood's practices undermined
the credibility of the ratings system used by the entertainment
industry to warn parents about the violent content of movies,
music and video games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
