<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Legislator Meets Latvian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIGA, Latvia, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese top legislator
Li Peng met here Monday with Latvian Prime Minister Andris Berzins
and the two discussed bilateral ties, the international and
regional situation and reached broad consensus.
</P>
<P>
Berzins said the stable and constructive ties between Latvia
and China have witnessed a sound development in recent years and
that Li's visit will give a vigorous momentum to the development.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress, said China highly values its relations with
Latvia, which commands great geographical importance in the
Baltics.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China's understanding of and support for the
Baltic states' aspirations "to return to Europe" and to join the
European Union (EU) because these are choices made in accordance
with their own conditions.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to see a stronger EU as one pole of a multi-polar
world," the Chinese leader said.
</P>
<P>
Berzins, for his part, said the Latvian people appreciate China
's kindness and friendly sentiments.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed his country's long-standing one-
China policy.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed his thanks for the stand. He stressed that
sticking to a one-China policy is the prerequisite and basis for
the stable and long-term development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Berzins said Latvia would like to strengthen its economic and
trade cooperation with China. He put forward some suggestions
concerning the utilization of Riga port and the Eurasia
Continental Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Li said China stands ready to explore new ways in strengthening
economic and trade cooperation with Latvia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
