<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Welcomes Postponement of Palestinian Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Moscow Monday welcomed a
decision taken by the Central Council of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization Sunday to put off the declaration of an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian leaders are well aware of the realities and
are waging a policy of resolving the Palestinian issue through
political dialogue," Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vasily Sredin,
presidential envoy in the Middle East, told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians have clearly called for continuation of talks
with Israel and confirmed their intention to reach an
understanding on a permanent status of Palestinian territories,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Palestine "did not take unilateral steps that would lead to
negative consequences for the peace process in the Middle East,"
Interfax quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moscow believes there is still a chance to reach a Palestinian-
Israeli agreement and this should be fully taken advantage of, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Sredin expressed his regret that Palestinians and Israelis "
still have serious differences over the entire spectrum of a
permanent settlement, in particular borders, settlements, refugees,
water resources and, the most sensitive issue, the status of East
Jerusalem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Barak to Rewrite Agenda to Save Political Future by Qi Deliang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The countdown for Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's political future begins Monday evening when
he returns home from the United Nations Millennium Summit in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Faced with domestic political crisis, Barak has to leave the
sweet memories of meetings with the world leaders in New York
behind and focus his attention on ways to resolve political
problems at home.
</P>
<P>
By October 30, when Israeli Knesset (parliament) reconvenes
after its three-month recess, Barak must form a coalition that in
the first week of November will be able to help him repulse a no-
confidence vote, push through the 2001 state budget and bury the
bill of dissolving the Knesset and holding early elections.
</P>
<P>
Barak is scheduled to hold urgent meetings shortly after his
return Monday with key members and cabinet ministers of his One
Israel to brief them on his U.S. trip and his political agenda that
he plans to rewrite.
</P>
<P>
But in reality, each political task is much grayer and
frustrating for him to handle.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the July Camp David peace talks with the
Palestinians, all the ultra-Orthodox parties including Shas, the
third largest party in Knesset, and National Religious Party (NRP)
left the coalition, making the government a minority one in the
parliament. Political differences with Shas also led to the quit of
the cabinet ministers of moderate Meretz, the key coalition partner
of One Israel.
</P>
<P>
Six weeks elapsed, Barak has not taken Meretz back yet. Meretz
leader Yossi Sarid accompanied Barak to the New York summit; but
Barak did not give a clear indication about Meretz's future,
forcing Sarid to declare that Meretz will neither join a coalition
that will not move the peace process forward, nor one that will
include the opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether Shas and NRP are willing to rejoin the
coalition. But what is sure is that a future minority government
formed with Meretz, the Center Party, Shinui (religious reform
party) and supported by 10 Arab Knesset members from outside will
be shaky at the mercy of the caprices of each individual lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
Barak's other option is to form a national unity government with
hawkish Likud, the opponent of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
To bring Likud into the coalition, Barak will have to publicly
declare the death of the peace process on both the Palestinian and
Syrian tracks. In so doing, Barak will lose American support, dig a
deep pit between himself and senior members of One Israel, and lose
support of all his voters. Barak won wide support in last year's
elections on a platform of making peace with Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Before going to New York last week, Barak initiated a "civil
reform" plan to finish formulating a constitution within one year,
which will include the abolition of the Religious Affairs Ministry,
introduction of civil marriage and letting all the state-funded
schools study three core subjects of English, mathematics and
civics.
</P>
<P>
In New York, he expanded his plan by calling for more public
transport and flight by Israel's national carrier El Al on Sabbath.
Traditionally, Jews refrain from any work on Sabbath, which runs
from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Barak's plan not only incurred disagreement within One Israel,
but angered the ultra-Orthodox parties. Shas and NRP have said
Barak was declaring a religious war within the country.
</P>
<P>
Barak's "civil reform" plan aims to prepare for new elections
and give a signal to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat that he will
focus on domestic straits instead of the peace talks. Political
observers here believe, however, that only a peace agreement with
the Palestinians will save Barak from political perdition.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Arafat held separate meetings in New York with U.S.
President Bill Clinton to chart a course for the peace talks to
proceed. On Sunday, the Palestinian leadership decided to postpone
the declaration of Palestinian statehood again and to have peace
talks with Israel for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
This allows more time for the peace talks to succeed. But the
future of Jerusalem, a holy city to Jews, Muslims and Christians,
remains a sticking point in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It had been the deal-breaker in the Camp David summit.
Palestinians want traditionally Arab East Jerusalem, captured by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast war, as the capital of their future
state, while Israel claims the whole of Jerusalem as its "eternal
and undivided" capital.
</P>
<P>
Barak suggested Sunday that he was willing to consider less than
full Israeli sovereignty over the site, provided it was not handed
to sole Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told Clinton last week in New York that he would accept "
Islamic sovereignty" over the holy site, under the auspices of
several Arab countries such as Jordan, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
If he could obtain a peace agreement with the Palestinians
favored by the Israeli public, Barak would regain his political
edge and could ask the Knesset to choose either a referendum or an
election centering on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak has to rewrite his political agenda as soon as possible by
taking measures to form a new coalition, push the budget through
the Knesset, handle properly the "civil reform" plan and speed up
peace talks with the Palestinians. Otherwise, his political future
will be in jeopardy and his government will be a goodby one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Pledges Cooperation With Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Cyprus are working
together to find a solution to the Cyprus issue and Greece supports
the island's accession to the European Union (EU), said Greece's
new ambassador to Cyprus on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at Cyprus' southern Larnaca airport, Ambassador
Christos Panagopoulos said the message he conveys from Athens is "
togetherness, further forging of national unanimity" and securing
cooperation between the governments of Greece and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island after a
failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the two
Cypriot communities have been held since last December, which aimed
at paving the way for substantive negotiations to reach a
settlement in Cyprus. The fourth round will open in New York on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus started substantive accession negotiations with the EU in
November 1998. It hopes to be admitted as an EU member by January
2003.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador noted that as long as Turkey sticks to its "
intransigent policy" on the issue, Greece must help Cyprus upgrade
its defense capability, in the context of a joint defense pact
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact signed in 1993, Greece will provide military
assistance to Cyprus in case the Mediterranean island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
The senior diplomat said that "the strategic aim is to obtain
such circumstances that will allow the survival of Cypriot
hellenism in conditions of security and future prosperity."
</P>
<P>
To this end, Athens and Nicosia have defined the U.N. Security
Council decisions on Cyprus as guidelines to achieve a solution,
which must provide for the reunification of the island, the
establishment of a bizonal, bicommunal federation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there is full cooperation between the two
governments to achieve this goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Backs Efforts to Stabilize Oil Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Oil-rich Saudi Arabia on
Monday reaffirmed its support to all efforts employed to stabilize
world oil markets.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made during a cabinet session chaired by King
Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz in the western Saudi city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Council of Ministers praised the cooperation at the
ministerial meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) in Vienna on Sunday, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil ministers agreed on a compromised agreement of
increasing their output by 800,000 barrels per day from October 1
to curb the runaway oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The new OPEC move was aimed at pushing prices down into its
preferred range of 22-28 U.S. dollars a barrel. Oil prices in
London recently soared to its 10-year high of over 33 dollars per
barrel.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, which sits on about 26 percent of the total world
oil reserves, has thrown its weight behind efforts exerted to cool
down high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to New York, Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah
Ibn Abdul-Aziz called for "stable prices to guarantee the interests
of both producers and consumers."
</P>
<P>
He said oil-producing countries must assume their
responsibilities with a view to bringing fairness to both producers
and consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
