<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Students Protest "IMF Intervention" in Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- University students in Ankara
and Istanbul on Monday protested the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for what they called intervention in Turkey's economy, and
rapped the government for submitting its economic policies to the
world body.
</P>
<P>
A group of students from Student Coordination of Ankara's
Universities came to the capital's Sakarya Avenue with banners,
shouting slogans against the IMF, Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Go away the IMF, this country is not for sale," students
shouted. The students later walked to the Human Rights Monument
located at Yuksel Avenue of the central city and then dispersed.
</P>
<P>
In Istanbul, a group of 30 protestors were taken into custody by
police after they attempted to hold a demonstration in front of the
U.S. Consulate.
</P>
<P>
The group comprising university and high school students was
stopped by police, and the students opened banners protesting the
IMF and threw eggs at the security forces who blocked them to
proceed further.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the police took some protestors into custody
and brought them to the Istanbul Security Directorate.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is implementing a three-year economic stability program
under the 4-billion-dollar stand-by deal signed with the IMF last
December.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year loan package approved by the IMF, Turkey
pledged to reduce its chronic inflation and budget deficits,
undertake a comprehensive privatization program and reform
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual inflation
rate stood at 68.9 percent in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the IMF Turkey-desk Chief Carlo Cottarelli led
a delegation to Turkey for the third regular review of the deal,
upon which the IMF board should release the fourth tranche of the 4
billion dollars stand-by loan -- around 300 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team inspected possible measures by the government on
monetary and fiscal policies for next year within the framework of
the 2001 budget plans.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Cottarelli expressed optimistic about the
privatization programme in the country, saying that it is possible
that further progress will be achieved in Turk Telekom sell-off and
other privatizations.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit defended the
governmental policies, saying that expressing concerns and putting
forward recommendations by international organizations from which
Turkey seeks help "are natural."
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the claim that the government's submission to
outside pressures, saying that "it is our state, together with the
relevant social groups, that determines the economic, social and
financial policies of Turkey." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
