<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Works to Win Understanding for "Social Plan" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is in favor of a "covenant" between religious and secular
Jews as he makes efforts to implement his "social reform agenda,"
the Prime Minister's Office said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A number of teams have been asked to draw up suggestions and
they have been working on the subject for a while, according to a
statement released by the office.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to reach an agreement on preserving the Jewish and
Zionist nature of the state alongside the modernization of the
country, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
While declining to predict how long it takes the prime minister
to reach the religious-secular "covenant," Baker David, a spokesman
for Barak's office, told Xinhua that it has always been Barak's
efforts to achieve an understanding between different sectors of
the society.
</P>
<P>
The purpose, said David, is to provide the secular population "
an opportunity to do what they have never done before," partly
referring to Barak's promise to allow buses to run on Sabbath so as
to carry some carless poor immigrants to the beach or other
recreational areas, and to allow the state-run airline El Al to
operate on Sabbath to facilitate its privatization.
</P>
<P>
That is part of his "civil agenda," David said, adding that the
ethic behind the agenda is to create an equitable, freer and
orderly society not at the expense of certain groups of the
population.
</P>
<P>
The social agenda, said the spokesman, reflects the prime
minister's long-time intentions to bridge social differences and
turn the society into a more tolerant one.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Minister of Science, Culture and Sports Matan
Vilnai said: "The government is able to raise several banners at
once...There is a close connection between social development and
the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Barak has been criticized for promoting his "secular
revolution," which came as a surprise in August, concerning
disbanding of the Ministry of Religous Affairs, allowing civil
marriages and imposing national service for all, including the
ultra-Orthodox yeshiva students and Arab Israeli youths.
</P>
<P>
The move was disliked by both the religious parties and Barak's
own Labor party, for fear that it might change the country's
religious status quo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Jewish leaders in New York on Sunday, Barak said he
will be absolutely committed to his "civil agenda" which is seen by
analysts as a path of escape that Barak has designed for himself in
case the peace talks with the Palestinians end in failure.
</P>
<P>
He told the Jewish leaders that the agenda intended to "set
right the presently distorted situation, which prevents large
sectors of the population from receiving services that a democratic
nation must provide its citizens."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Barak stressed that the current effort in the
peace process was a historic opportunity that must not be missed.
</P>
<P>
Returning from his trip to the United Nations on Monday, Barak
will be faced with uphill tasks of reshuffling his coalition and
pushing ahead the stalled peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
