<HEADLINE> 24 Iranians Sentenced for Taking Part in Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian court has sentenced
24 people to one to five years in prison for taking part in riots
and attacks on public buildings in March in the northwestern city
of Khalkhal, a judiciary official announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 52 people were tried for their involvement in the
riots, which were sparked by a decision by the conservative
Guardians Council (GC) to annul the results of the February 18
Majlis (parliament) elections in the town.
</P>
<P>
But only 24 of them were found guilty of damaging public
properties, and the others were acquitted, said Amir Sohrab Beig,
head of the justice department of Ardabil Province, where the town
is located.
</P>
<P>
The official said that those convicted have 20 days to appeal to
have their lawsuits forwarded to the provincial appeals court.
</P>
<P>
Pro-reform allies of President Mohammad Khatami won an
overwhelming victory in the February elections, ending the long-
time conservative domination in the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
But the conservative GC, the top supervisor of the election,
cancelled election results in a number of constituencies, and in
some cases even replaced reformist winners with their conservative
rivals. The measure sparked protests in the related constituencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
