<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Not to Pay for Palestinian Delay of Statehood: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami Monday welcomed the Palestinian decision to
postpone the declaration of statehood, but refused to regard it as
a favor that Israel should pay for in return.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said he did not see any change in Palestinian National
Authority Yasser Arafat's attitude in the peace talks. Arafat wants
an agreement and "their idea to postpone the declaration means they
want to exhaust" the possibility for striking a peace deal, he told
Xinhua at a press conference in the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"To make it very clear," said he, "the fact that they postponed
the unilateral declaration should not be seen an ingredient in the
negotiations. This is not an item Israel should pay for in terms of
assets of negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"This is a free decision taken by the Palestinians after having
evaluated all the constraints that existed. We of course think it
is commendable that they decided to postpone. It is good for the
process."
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami told reporters that whether the peace talks will achieve
progress "depends much on the attitude" of the negotiators. He said
that if both sides would "build on the impressions that we have
gathered from Camp David," there is still hope for progress in the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Asked by Xinhua about whether the two sides would strive for a
framework deal instead of a comprehensive final accord considering
the difficulties involved in the final status talks, Ben-Ami said "
a framework agreement is feasible," but at the same time, he
stressed that "being feasible does not mean he (Arafat) will take
the final decisions."
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami praised Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's courage as
shown in the Camp David summit and called on Arafat to exercise the
faculties of leadership when the moment of truth arrives.
</P>
<P>
The acting foreign minister, who will leave for U.N. General
Assembly on Tuesday, said that Arafat's delay of statehood
declaration gave the peace process "a new lease on life." He said
that the two parties should do their utmost to exhaust the
possibility within the time frame that is allowed.
</P>
<P>
However, he played down expectations for a major breakthrough in
the future talks which will be given only four or five weeks of
time, saying that "there is no much or excessive room for hope."
</P>
<P>
He said Israel has supported the U.S. proposals on delaying the
Jerusalem issue which is the major stumbling block for the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
According to their Sharm el Sheikh accord signed last September,
the two sides should complete a permanent peace deal on all final
status issues which also include borders, water, Jewish settlements
and Palestinian refugees, by the mutually-agreed deadline of
September 13.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bridging ideas on deferring the negotiations of the Old
City in Jerusalem, or the entire Jerusalem have been rejected by
the Palestinians who want to build an independent state with East
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The Old city in the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem, home to
the Temple Mount, the most sacred in Judaism, and a number of holy
shrines of Islam, was captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said that following the U.N. Millennium Summit where U.
S. President Bill Clinton made intensive mediation efforts to help
strike a peace deal, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators resumed
talks on Sunday in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the negotiations have never stopped since the July Camp
David summit, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak hailed the Palestinian postponement of
statehood as a "positive step," saying that the historic
opportunity must not be missed.
</P>
<P>
Both Israelis and Palestinians have seen October as their
deadline for further negotiations considering the fact that by the
time U.S. congress will go into recess so that it will not be
possible to endorse the massive aid packages needed to back a peace
deal, and that the Israeli parliament will reopen probably with a
wave of no-confidence votes for Barak's minority government.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who has been trying to strike a peace deal with the
Palestinians to fulfil his major election pledge 18 months ago, has
delayed the reshuffling of his government, waiting to see in what
direction the peace process will go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
