<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Hold Talks on Palestinian-Israeli Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
began talks with visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Monday
evening on future policy in negotiations with Israel that resumed
Monday after a six-week hiatus.
</P>
<P>
The meeting started immediately after Arafat's arrival at the
Borg al Arab airport, west of Egypt's Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has frequently visited Egypt to consult Mubarak, the key
mediator in the Palestinian-Israeli peace process, strategies in
dealing with Israel. The current visit came one day after the
Palestine Central Council (PCC) decided to delay the declaration of
an independent state while Arafat agreed to have peace talks with
Israel for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had earlier said amid a deadlock peace to proclaim an
independent state as early as on September 13, the deadline set
with Israel for a permanent peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders were expected to focus on the outcome of the
just concluded meeting of the PCC, which will meet again by
November 15 to consider when to declare statehood, Palestinian
Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qedra said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is reportedly to go on to Oman on Tuesday for a meeting
with Sultan Qabus Bin Said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have underlined the importance to
strengthen consultation and coordination with Arab leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
