<HEADLINE> Iranians Suspected of Killing Opposition Figures to Be Tried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen Iranians will soon
stand trial for alleged involvement in murdering several opposition
figures and dissident intellectuals in Tehran at the end of 1998,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tehran's military court has issued indictment against the 18
people and a court hearing will be held, said Abdol Reza Izadpanah,
a judiciary official in charge of social affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said the defendants have 10 days to introduce defense lawyers
to the court, otherwise they will be provided with court-appointed
lawyers. The official, however, did not disclose the status of the
accused.
</P>
<P>
Darius Forouhar, a veteran political activist who headed the
Iran Nation Party, his wife, and several dissident writers were
mysteriously killed in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Intelligence Ministry had admitted some of its own agents
had been involved in the killings, which shocked the Iranian
society and forced former Intelligence Minister Qobanali Dorri
Najafabadi to resign.
</P>
<P>
The case also led to the suicide in prison of Former Deputy
Intelligence Minister for Political and Security Affairs Saeed
Emami, who was arrested last year for his major role in the
political killings. 
</P>
