<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will soon deliver two mobile power transmission
units to Lebanon as part of the efforts to help its reconstruction,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The first unit will be delivered to Lebanon next week and the
other next month, said Bahman Masoudi, deputy head of the Power
Generation and Distribution Center.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new equipment is to replace those damaged
during Israeli bombardment of Lebanon early this year. The two
units cost between 1.5 to 2 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Nearly 1 billion dirhams (273.2 million U.S.
dollars) will be spent on improving and upgrading Dubai's road
network this year, the official WAM news agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, more than 400 million dirhams (109.3 million dollars)
will be spent on sewerage and drainage projects in the emirate.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 970.04 million dirhams (265.03 million
dollars) have been earmarked for roads, including the stage four of
Dubai city's ring road and 412 million dirhams (112.6 million
dollars) on expanding the Al Aweer Sewage Treatment, and completing
the city's rain water drainage network at a cost of 300 million
dirhams (81.96 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The outlay more than doubled the 538.2 million dirhams (147
million dollars) spent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's trade deficit during the first five months of
this year widened as the kingdom's imports more than doubled its
exports, the central bank said in its monthly bulletin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The import volume stood at 1.1 billion Jordanian dinars (1.54
billion U.S. dollars) as against the export volume of 418.9 million
dinars (586.5 million dollars) during the January-May period, the
bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
Medical and pharmaceutical products topped the kingdom's export
list during the first five months, while transport equipments, cars
and spare parts accounted for the major part of its imports.
</P>
<P>
Iraq remained Jordan's largest trading partner during the
period, and the kingdom's imports from Iraq amounted to 195 million
dinars (273 million dollars), while its exports to Iraq at 47
million dinars (65.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A two-day Gulf-Euro summit will be held in Dubai of
the United Arab Emirates on October 8-9, reported the official WAM
news agency on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The summit will discuss ways of strengthening long-term economic
ties between the two blocs.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti government has approved a project on
building two power generating stations at a total cost of 2.6
billion U.S. dollars to meet the growing domestic demand for
electricity.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be carried out in partnership with the private
sector, would involve a gas-operated station at a capacity of 1,000
megawatt and a steam-operated station at a capacity of 2,500
megawatt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
