<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Blood Transfusion Workshop Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A four-week quality management
training workshop for blood transfusion service providers in the
African region started here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, the first of its kind, is held following a
meeting of experts last year where the need for quality management
in blood transfusion services was emphasized, said director for
blood safety and clinical technology of the World Health
Organization (WHO) Jean Emmanuel.
</P>
<P>
The workshop would cover the need to ensure safe blood donors,
quality storage, quality transportation of blood and the correct
blood type, the director said, explaining that the quality
management project has various components which include training
and establishment of laboratories.
</P>
<P>
"If we train people, they will go back to their countries with
knowledge to ensure that these things are put in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said similar workshops would be carried out in other parts
of the world including Asia and America. Zimbabwe has been
selected as a venue for the training because it is a collaborative
center for work carried out by the organization in the region, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe is the only country in Africa which has since 1994
been a collaborative center for WHO's blood transfusion services,
but we hope to get more countries if they meet certain standards,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
About 30 participants from Kenya, Botswana, Uganda, South
Africa, Eritrea, Zambia, Malawi, Ghana and Nigeria are attending
the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the workshop, Zimbabwe's Health and Child Welfare
Minister Timothy Stamps reiterated the need to teach the public on
the importance of blood and its safety.
</P>
<P>
Quality control of blood is essential in the wake of the HIV/
AIDS pandemic, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO, each year unsafe blood transfusion and
injection practices accounted for 80,000 to 160,000 HIV infections
in the developing world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
