<HEADLINE> Portuguese-Speaking Countries Urged to Update Customs Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Finance Minister
Joaquim David Monday urged member states of the Community of the
Portuguese-speaking Countries (CPLP) to modernize their customs
services to fight against tax evasions and other forms of trans-
border crimes.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of bases for mutual assistance among the
customs administrations of CPLP member countries is of extreme
importance for fighting trans-border crimes like drug trafficking,
he said while opening the 16th Conference of General Directors of
the Customs of CPLP here in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, with "the Customs Facing Challenges in
the Second Millennium" as the theme, is expected to discuss issues
concerning technical cooperation, training of customs
professionals and mutual assistance among the CPLP member states
in customs services.
</P>
<P>
Issues related to the prevention of customs infractions and
combats against illicit drug trafficking are also top on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Attending the conference are delegates from Angola, Brazil,
Cape Verde, Guinea-Bissau, Mozambique, Portugal, Sao Tome and
Principe. 
</P>
