<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Involve Communities in Handling Airport Emergencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The eastern and
southern African countries have been urged to involve communities
surrounding airports in handling emergencies which the airport
authorities in the region can not manage on their own.
</P>
<P>
"Handling of airport emergencies requires a coordinated program
between the airport and the surrounding community," said Salim
Msoma, permanent secretary in Tanzanian Ministry of Communications
and Transport, on Monday while speaking at the opening ceremony of
a five-day international workshop on aerodrome emergency planning
in the eastern and southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the airport authorities in the region can not on their
own have the necessary human or material resources needed to
handle emergencies, especially of great magnitude.
</P>
<P>
A discussion on how to handle aircraft and other airport
emergencies will enhance safety in air travel, he said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the International Civil Aviation
Organization in conjunction with the Tanzanian Airports Authority
and attended by delegates from more than 16 African countries, is
intended to review the status of aerodrome emergency planning in
the region and stress on the importance of airports emergency
procedures.
</P>
<P>
It will also stress the need to conduct regular emergency
drills to test the efficiency of those procedures and the
readiness of various state organs in implementing them, organizers
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
