<HEADLINE> Nigerian Aviation Industry Asks for U.S. Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Ministry of Aviation
Monday called on its U. S. counterpart to provide assistance for
the country's fledgling aviation industry and make it benefit from
the Open Sky Agreement signed lately by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Meeting a U. S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)
delegation in the capital Abuja, Nigeria's Aviation Minister Kema
Chikwe said it is necessary, at the current stage, to accelerate
the accreditation by the FAA to Nigerian airlines and
administrative agencies for their operation in the U. S. airspace.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's aviation industry resumed in August direct flights to
the United States after long-time suspension. The country needs to
improve its airspace management to meet international standards,
Chikwe said.
</P>
<P>
On his side, Edward Jones, head of the U. S. delegation and FAA
representative in Africa, said he has come with various
specialists to find out what assistance the FAA could provide for
his Nigerian colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The Open Sky Agreement, which aims to allow business carriers
of both countries to operate freely in the two countries' airspace,
was signed during U. S. President Bill Clinton's visit to Nigeria
late August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
