<HEADLINE> Liberal Democrats: Britain Almost Meeting Tests to Join Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The five tests laid down by
Chancellor Golden Brown for UK entry into the euro were "in the
process of being met," according to a report commissioned by the
Liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The commission of 14 economists, which included former member
of the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee, said UK entry
was "perfectly feasible" but the government must prepare the
ground now.
</P>
<P>
The report came Monday as the Institute of Directors said
Britain was "a long way off" achieving convergence with the euro
zone. In its report for the Liberal Democrats, the commission said
the business cycles of the two economic areas were converging.
</P>
<P>
There was no reason to believe that the UK's financial or
economic structure made adoption of the euro uniquely problematic,
it added.
</P>
<P>
The commission said it was vital the government adopted a
timetable to ensure UK full membership of the euro before a
general election to prevent a political campaign destabilizing the
pound.
</P>
<P>
It identified a range of DM2.45 to DM2.84 against the German
mark at which the UK economy could compete. This compares with a
closing rate last week of DM3.21. "Sterling remains overvalued
against the euro at the levels prevailing during the summer of
2000," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
