<HEADLINE> Canadian Students Rated 2nd in Web Use Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian students rank second
in Web use with 74 percent of them having Internet access at
school and 71 percent having it at home, The Globe and Mail
newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a survey by the Angus Reid Group involving 10,000
students aged 12 to 24 from 16 countries and regions, the
newspaper said Canadian students are increasingly dependent on the
Internet, second only to their Swedish counterparts, of whom 78
percent access the Internet at school and 80 percent at home.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan goes the third with the Internet access available for 63
percent of students at school and 45 percent at home.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, 59 percent of the students enjoy the
Internet access at school and 68 percent at home.
</P>
<P>
Britain has a similar rate with 59 percent of students offered
the access at school and 49 percent at home.
</P>
<P>
There has been a jump in the number of Web users in Canada,
where the proportion of homes with one regular Internet user grew
to 41.8 percent in 1999, up from the previous year's 35.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
