<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 Victim Found in Italian Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Rain finally tapered off in the
Italian southern town of Soverato Monday, allowing rescue and
relief teams to continue their efforts which led to the discovery
of the 12th confirmed victim from Sunday's flash flood.
</P>
<P>
The Italian news agency Ansa reported that local police are
still uncertain over the exact number of people who may still be
missing but, based on an earlier estimate, they should be at least
four.
</P>
<P>
The uncertainty stemmed from the fact that it was not known
exactly how many were at the camp when the flood hit just before
dawn Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor's office in the region of Calabria has impounded
administrative documents in the town to Soverato, including the
license for the camp to operate, in order to ascertain whether the
campground was in line with the law and why some 45 percent of the
site itself was allowed to be in the river basin itself.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's flash flood came several weeks ahead of the
traditional period of flooding in Italy, October-November.
</P>
<P>
Available documents showed that over the past 80 years floods
have struck 169 towns in Calabria, out of a total of over 15,000
floods and 6,456 municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Venice is the Italian city which has experienced the greatest
number of flood incidents during this period, and Veneto is the
Italian region with the highest number of recorded floods of 2,131.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
