<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Vietnam Sign Pacts on Energy Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Vietnam signed a
package of agreements here Monday after a meeting of Russian Prime
Minister Mikhail Kasyanov and his Vietnamese counterpart, Phan Van
Khai, to enhance bilateral trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on cooperation in the fuel and energy sphere,
including the joint production of oil and gas in Vietnam and in
the joint construction of Vietnam's first oil refinery.
</P>
<P>
In particular, an oil and gas contract was signed between
PetroVietnam, a Vietnamese oil and gas corporation, and Russia's
largest gas company Gazprom and Russia's overseas oil enterprise
Zarubezhneft to exploit Vietnam's continental shelf.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between the two countries in the oil and gas
industry is developing very actively.... The contract signed today
indicates that Gazprom is joining this cooperation and starting
its work in Vietnam," Kasyanov told the press after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-Vietnamese joint venture Vietsovpetro is one of the
most promising projects and ranks among the world's best oil
companies, he said, noting that the construction of Vietnam's
first oil refinery has begun with Russian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The sides have identical approaches to ways of settling
international problems and to economic partnership. Russia will
adhere to the principle of broadening strategic cooperation with
Vietnam, Kasyanov stressed.
</P>
<P>
The premiers also discussed the problem of Vietnam's debt to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
"This issue has come to its logical completion. This problem
should be turned into a mechanism of cooperation," said Kasyanov.
</P>
<P>
Phan arrived in Moscow for an official visit Sunday afternoon.
Tuesday, he will meet with Russian President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese premier will also meet with Russian State Duma (
lower house of parliament) Chairman Gennady Seleznyov and Chairman
of the Federation Council (upper chamber) Yegor Stroyev, as well
as Russian and Vietnamese business people, the Russian Foreign
Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
Russia's arms supply to Vietnam may be also one of the items on
the agenda of Phan Van Khai's talks in Moscow this week.
</P>
<P>
Thursday, Phan will travel from Moscow to Minsk for a visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
