<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Lift Oil Output Under OPEC Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran will increase its oil
output to 3.84 million barrels per day as of October 1 in
accordance with its new quota within the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), an Oil Ministry official said here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members, excluding Iraq, agreed in their Vienna meeting on
Sunday to add 800,000 barrels to their current oil production
ceiling of 25.4 million barrels per day as of October 1, said
Hossein Kazempour Ardebili, senior advisor to Iranian Oil Minister
Bijan Namdar Zanganeh.
</P>
<P>
He told the official IRNA news agency that with OPEC's new
production ceiling up to 26.2 million barrels per day, Iran's share
in the amount would rise to 3.84 million barrels per day from the
current 2.72 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of OPEC's latest production hike, Ardebili said
the increase will bring oil prices down to some extent.
</P>
<P>
Although OPEC members had raised their production ceiling twice
since March, oil prices were still very high, surpassing 30 U.S.
dollars per barrel in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Ardebili said that demand for OPEC's oil in the last quarter of
2000 is expected to be around 28.9 million barrels per day, less
than the 26.2 million barrels approved by OPEC plus Iraq's daily
production of 3 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the surplus will be stocked because the global
demand for oil is less than the total oil production of OPEC and
non-OPEC producers in the fourth quarter of the current year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
