<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Urges to Enhance Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Commerce, Trade and
Industry Minister William Harrington said Monday there is need for
greater regional integration if the region is to improve its
economic performance.
</P>
<P>
Harrington made the remarks here at the opening ceremony of the
sixth meeting of the Trade and Customs FTA (Free Trade Area)
Committee.
</P>
<P>
He noted that African countries have not yet succeeded in
improving their economies as shown by the levels of poverty,
infant mortality, life expectancy and industrial development.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said ever since its inception, the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) had made
tremendous strides in the quest for greater economic integration,
adding that the region was moving fast towards the establishment
of the FTA next month.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia had already published its legal instrument for
the zero rating tariffs to be applied on reciprocal basis from
October 31, urging other member countries to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia recognizes the challenges of regional integration and
wishes to benefit from the wider market the FTA will create. It is
only in this way can we move our people to a better world," he
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha
called for commitment from member countries to ensure successful
implementation of the FTA.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha also called on member states to guard against the "
catch up" theory, which was based on the premise that the region
should industrialize first before integrating, and catch up later.
</P>
<P>
This theory was going to be risky given the realities that
obtained in the region and the global dynamics, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
