<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truckers' Protest Paralyzes Belgian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Belgian truck drivers
angered by rising oil prices continued their protest Monday to
force the government into accepting their demands for a price cut
on diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred truck drivers blocked main roads leading to
downtown Brussels to press for lower fuel taxes and lower prices
for oil-reliant products and services.
</P>
<P>
Taxi drivers and tour bus operators joined the protest on
Sunday. Overnight negotiations between protesters and the
government failed to yield any results.
</P>
<P>
Truckers also blockaded Belgium's largest oil refinery
Totalfina in Feluy, Hainault, preventing tankers from getting new
supplies. They also blockaded the Esso depot in the southern town
of Tournai and blocked petrol distributors in the west from
replenishing their supplies.
</P>
<P>
The drivers vowed to continue the protest unless their demands
were met. They claim diesel fuel prices have increased by half
since the beginning of 1999, which is threatening their business.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the problem is being felt elsewhere in Europe, they
demanded immediate action by the European Union. Their action is
amid a wave of similar protests across Europe.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Belgium's Secretary of State
responsible for energy Olivier Deleuze proposed Monday to offer
the country's 100,000 poor families a total of 1,000 liters of
free heating oil this winter.
</P>
<P>
He added that the oil sector should pay the bill to offset the
impact by the price hike on these families.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
agreed in Vienna to raise oil production by 800,000 barrels a day.
The move has brought the price of oil down slightly on the
international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
