<HEADLINE> GCC Army Chiefs to Discuss Military Cooperation Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Army Chiefs of Staff
of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states will meet in the Saudi
capital of Riyadh Tuesday to discuss issues concerning military and
defense cooperation among member nations.
</P>
<P>
A GCC military source in Riyadh said that the meeting will
follow up on the implementation of projects, plans and joint
military training decided by GCC leaders during their 20th summit
held in Riyadh last November.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting will discuss the establishment of a security
belt among the GCC states, the source said, quoted by the Kuwait
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Countries of the six-member GCC -- Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates -- have agreed to build
an early warning network at a cost of 80 million U.S. dollars by
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
They have also agreed to establish a unified contact system
worth 70 million dollars to exchange information and data between
Gulf operation rooms.
</P>
<P>
As these projects were originally recommended by U.S. defense
officials who believed the GCC states still "face potential missile
attacks from regional countries such as Iran and Iraq," both of the
projects will be built with the help of Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
