<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Oil Prices to Erode Thailand's Mooncake Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Rising global oil prices will
hit Thailand's mooncake market hard, as the psychological effect
of dearer petrol causes consumers to buy fewer cakes, a report
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the Thai Farmers Bank research center
suggested the runaway oil prices would generate psychological
effects on buyers and the number of mooncakes purchased would drop.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was based on a poll of 1,142 mooncake
enthusiasts, revealed most consumers polled planned to buy at
least one fewer cake this year than last year.
</P>
<P>
Although the total number of mooncakes purchased this year is
expected to fall, hard-core Moon Goddess worshippers will buy just
as many treats as in 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Mooncake producers can help insure themselves against decreased
consumer spending by expanding their selling hours, using more
attractive packaging, making more varieties of cakes and adding
more sugar to the cakes, so that more people use the items not
only as ceremonial objects but also as desserts, the report said.
</P>
<P>
These preventative measure could "automatically expand the
market base" of the mooncake industry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) agreed
Sunday to boost daily global crude oil output by three per cent,
or 800,000 barrels, in a bid to ease soaring prices which has
sparked worldwide concern and protests in Europe.
</P>
<P>
But Western nations said the decision would be insufficient.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is particularly vulnerable to changes in world oil
prices, since the kingdom is highly dependent on oil. Oil
consumption in Thailand rose by nearly 80 percent between 1990 and
1998, according to the U.S. investment banking company Merrill
Linch.
</P>
<P>
The company forecasts that Thailand's growth rate will be
shaved by one percentage point or more in 2001 due largely to
higher import prices.
</P>
<P>
Oil accounts for close to 61 percent of Thailand's primary
energy consumption and natural gas 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country imported 168 billion baht (4.2 billion U.S. dollars)
worth of oil last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
