<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeeping Troops to Monitor Ethio-Eritrean Ceasefire in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
peacekeeping troops will start monitoring in October the
implementation of the ceasefire agreement signed by Ethiopia and
Eritrea in June after more than two years of bloody war, the U.N.
sources said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the U.N. peacekeeping mission along the
border between the two countries will be completed in October,
said the sources who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. announced in August that it was sending 100 liaison
officers each to Ethiopia and Eritrea to make the necessary
arrangements for the deployment of 4,200 peacekeepers to monitor
the ceasefire between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least 19 countries from Africa, Europe,
Asia and Latin America were ready to contribute troops to the U.N.
Peacekeeping Mission in Ethiopia and Eritrea (UNMEE), which will
be deployed in the 25-kilometer "security zone" inside Eritrean
territory.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 70 Ethiopian military officers have
received orientation training to assist the U.N. peacekeeping
mission, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
