</P>
<P>
-- Los Alamos physicist Wen Ho Lee has agreed to plead guilty
to a single felony count of improperly retaining classified
nuclear weapons data and could be released from jail Monday if a
federal judge in Albuquerque accepts a plea agreement negotiated
between Lee's attorneys and a team of prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
-- Responding to global fears about a looming energy crisis,
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed Monday to
raise daily production by 800,000 barrels in a bid to bring down
increased crude oil prices and avert a heating fuel shortage this
winter.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The story of the Firestone tire debacle, blamed for as many
as 150 deaths around the world, is one of missed hints, lost
opportunities and unsolved mysteries, a review of more than 100
company and government documents showed. Another hearing in
Congress will be held Tuesday on the issue.
</P>
<P>
-- Bowing to international pressure, Palestinian leaders
decided at a meeting on Sunday night, as expected, to postpone a
declaration of statehood and re-commit themselves to the Middle
East peace effort despite deeply deadlocked negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Antitrust regulators are expected to approve Covisint, a
huge online parts exchange established by the Big-Three auto
makers. Covisint could wield purchasing power of up to 240 billion
dollars a year. Over a dozen major parts suppliers have agreed to
join it.
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton proposed to spend about 1.6 billion dollars to help
communities recover from forest fires that have scorched more than
6.5 million acres of land in the West this summer. The plan would
include thinning millions of acres of federal forests as
precaution against future blazes. Clinton also announced about 40
million dollars in funds for 90 restoration projects in the region.
</P>
