<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary's Inflation to Increase Due to Rising Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's annual inflation
rate is expected to reach 9 percent this year, 0.5 percentage
points higher than expected, due to the recent increase in oil
prices on the international market, economy experts said.
</P>
<P>
The price of oil per barrel in the international market rose
from 15-17 U.S. dollars last year to an average of 30 dollars at
present, which is expected to push the country's inflation rate to
9 percent this year, the Magyar Tavirati Irodaise (Hungarian News
Agency) quoted experts on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rocketing oil prices, however, will have a limited impact on
the Hungarian economy as the country's industries have gone
through large-scale restructuring in recent years, resulting in a
decreasing demand for energy.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's demand for energy has dropped by 25 percent during
the past 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
