<HEADLINE> Manila Still Working for Release of Hostages: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday that it continues to work for safe release of the remaining
Filipino hostage taken from the Malaysian resort island of Sipadan,
and 13 evangelists held by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Robert Aventajado, chief government negotiator with
Abu Sayyaf, said in a radio interview that President Joseph
Estrada wants to make sure all the hostages are released safely,
regardless of nationality.
</P>
<P>
"We have not forgotten Filipino hostage Roland Ullah. He is
still in Patikul (on Jolo island in Sulu province), and we are
negotiating with another faction of the Abu Sayyaf holding him. We
hope to get him out in a few days," Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said negotiations are taking place for the release
of evangelist Wilde Almeda and his 12 followers, who went
voluntarily to the rebels' jungle lair to pray for release of the
21 hostages abducted from Malaysia's Sipadan island in late April.
</P>
<P>
Except for Filipino Ullah who is still held captive, the other
20 Sipadan hostages, including 10 foreign tourists, have all been
freed.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said it is likely that a "development fund" would be
given to the Abu Sayyaf in exchange for the release of Almeda and
his followers.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Ullah and Almeda's group, two French journalists are
still being held hostage by the Abu Sayyaf faction headed by
Ghalib Andang (Commander Robot).
</P>
<P>
"We are timing our move so as not to expose the hostages to any
danger," Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Abu Sayyaf faction headed by Robot will not
release all the hostages immediately because of fears of a
military attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
