<HEADLINE> South-East Asia TB Control Training Course Begins in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The fourth South-East Asian
training course on Tuberculosis (TB) control began here Monday to
enhance the managerial capability of the illness in the Southeast
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the course, Dirgha Bam, director of SAARC (South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) TB Center, said as
countries in the region are the home for nearly 38 percent of the
total TB patients in the world, emphasis should be given in the
directly observed treatment short-course (DOTS) method -- the "
best and proven way of controlling TB".
</P>
<P>
During the 12-day training, participants will be taught the
necessary managerial skills, laboratory and drug administration
management and systematic follow-up and evaluation of TB patients.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 24 managers working in the TB control field from
Bangladesh, Bhutan, Democratic People's Republic of Korea, India,
Indonesia, Myanmar, Nepal and Thailand are attending the training
course.
</P>
<P>
The training is co-organized by Nepali Health Ministry and
SAARC TB Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
