<HEADLINE> Singapore to Give Compensations to Telecom Players SingTel, StarHub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's top two telecom
players, SingTel and StarHub, will get a total of 1.9 billion
Singapore dollars (about 1.1 billion U.S. dollars) from the
government as a compensation for the accelerated freeing-up of the
telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
SingTel will get 859 million Singapore dollars (about 499
million U.S. dollars) and StarHub 1.082 billion Singapore dollars
(about 629 million U.S. dollars), the Information Development
Authority (IDA) announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have accepted the compensations, IDA said.
</P>
<P>
"Compensation is being offered in recognition of the business
and investment plans that both operators had made for duopoly-
based public telecommunications services market, prior to the
announcement of full market liberalization," IDA said.
</P>
<P>
IDA said that the government is committed to introducing full
market competition in the telecommunications sector as competition
spurs innovation, raises efficiency, improves services and lowers
prices.
</P>
<P>
Yeo Cheow Tong, minister for Communications and Information
Technology, announced early this year that the government will
accelerate the full liberalization of the telecommunications
sector by two years, from April 1, 2000 to April 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
Yeo also said that SingTel and StarHub will get compensations
for the impact of the early introduction of freeing-up measures.
</P>
<P>
He said the advance of full market competition by two years was
necessary because rapid changes in the global telecommunications
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
