<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One More Tutsi Party Signs Burundi Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Pang Yong
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- One of the four Tutsi
parties which refused to sign the peace agreement aimed at ending
Burundi's seven-year civil war last month put its signature on the
document here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a brief ceremony held at the Mwalimu Nyerere Foundation,
where the Burundi peace facilitation team is based, Godefroy
Hakizimana, chairman of the Social Democratic Party (PSD), signed
on behalf of his party the Burundi Peace and Reconciliation Accord,
which was drawn up after over two years of marathon talks.
</P>
<P>
However, three of the remaining parties from the minority Tutsi
group, namely ANADDE, RADES and PIT, who were expected to sign on
Monday together with PSD, did not appear at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they have asked to see the international facilitator
Nelson Mandela in Johannesburg, South Africa, because they would
like to have some clarifications on the agreement, said Mark
Bomani, head of the facilitation team and top aid of Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has agreed to meet with them on Wednesday, Bomani said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope after they have been given the clarification they are
seeking, they'll be able to sign. Because we have indicated before,
Wednesday is the last day for signing this document," Bomani said
before the PSD chairman put his signatures on the document.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that these documents will be delivered to
the four depositories, namely the Secretary General of the U.N.,
the Secretary General of the OAU, the National Assembly of Burundi
and the Nyerere Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"So it will not be possible for anyone to sign these documents
after Wednesday. Signing of these documents will be closed," said
Bomani.
</P>
<P>
If those who have not signed by then wish to join the process,
he said, they have to apply to the signatories, to get their
agreement to add their signatures to their agreement.
</P>
<P>
Bomani disclosed his team will convene a meeting of all
signatories on September 25 in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha,
where the signatories will talk about the implementation of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
"We'll discuss the various measures that need to be taken for
the implementations. For example, under this document, within 60
days of signing the document, the parties are invited to nominate
their representatives in the National Assembly, three
representatives each, Bomani said.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to make nominations to the government
and will have to appoint the Implementation Monitoring Committee,
Bomani added.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace accord was signed in Arusha on August 28 this
year amid much confusion. Thirteen out of the 19 parties involved
in the peace talks signed with reservation, after considerable
pressure from the international community on the ensemble of
Burundi warring parties.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, mediator of the peace accord, has called on
representatives of Burundian government and the main rebel groups
to meet in Nairobi, Kenya, on September 20 to work out details yet
solved in the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Tutsis dominate the army and the economy of Hutu-majority
Burundi. Civil war broke out in 1993 upon the assassination of
the central African nation's first and only democratically elected
president Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu. Fighting since then has killed
200,000 people in the nation of roughly 6 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
