<HEADLINE> S. Leone Calls for International Help Over Refugee Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has called for
international assistance to help solve the pressing issue of
refugees being driven out from Guinea, according to reports
reaching here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's Ambassador to Guinea Sheku Ba Saccoh was quoted
as saying in Monrovia, capital of Guinea, that the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) should adopt some emergency
measures to address the horrifying situation in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
Saccoh said refugees from Liberia and Sierra Leone had been
thrown out of their homes in Guinea in the middle of the rainy
season and were desperate for shelter.
</P>
<P>
The rounding-up of refugees began last Saturday after a speech
by Guinean President Lansana Conte in which he accused the
displaced people of helping armed dissidents who had been
responsible for the cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about half a million refugees fled Liberia
and Sierra Leone and stormed into the neighboring Guinea during
the civil wars in the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The Guinean authorities began the crackdown on foreigners
following the president's speech in the capital Conakry and the
Guinean civilians also joined enthusiastically in hunting down the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
About 700 frightened people stormed into the Sierra Leonean
Embassy and spent the night in the embassy compound after being
driven out from homes by their landlords, or told by neighborhood
chiefs that they were no longer wanted in the area, said the
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Sierra Leoneans seem to have been the main
targets, because Liberians living in Conakry are much less
obviously foreign, being from the same tribes and speaking the
same languages as the local population.
</P>
<P>
Guinea has allegedly accusing Sierra Leone and Liberia of
supporting armed bandits in the cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
