<HEADLINE> Software Company Launches .net Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A Beijing software company
claims today that it has conducted a "successful experiment" in
the upgrading of the industry by linking traditional software
products with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The new software, Kingsoft.net2001, developed by Kingsoft
Company, will make its debut on the Beijing market on September 23
this year, Kingsoft's chairman Lei Jun announced here today.
</P>
<P>
He described the software as "an electronic encyclopedia",
saying that the new software will enable users to download new
words directly from the Internet "with a click of the mouse."
</P>
<P>
"Kingsoft's long-term development strategy is focused on the
Internet," he said, adding that some 12 million Internet surfers
are currently using Kingsoft2000.
</P>
<P>
The company also announced the opening of a new website, www.
iciba.net, saying that it would facilitate the downloading of
words and on-line searching.
</P>
<P>
Kingsoft.net2001 contains more than seven million expressions
and over 2000 pictures. Three versions, a Chinese, English and
Japanese, will be available on the market soon, according to Lei.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Kingsoft introduced its Kingsoft2000 version and sold
one million copies at 28 yuan each in less than three months.
</P>
<P>
Yin Zhihe, executive chairman of the Beijing Software Industry
Association, said that China's software industry is still "at a
nascent stage", with sales accounting for less than 1 percent of
the country's gross domestic product. Seventy percent of the
software products sold in the Chinese market are foreign products.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government introduced favorable policies this year
in intellectual property protection, tax reductions and in its
anti-piracy campaign to support the sector's development, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
