<HEADLINE> HK MTR Moves Toward Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Regional government Donald Tsang
announced Monday that the government will privatize the Mass
Transit Railway Corp. (MTR) by selling 20 percent of its stake.
</P>
<P>
The MTR Privatization Share Offer, structured as a global
offering, will be aimed at retail investors in Hong Kong and
domestic and international professional and institutional
investors, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The initial price range has been set at 8 to 9.38 HK dollars
per share for the initial public offering (IPO) which will open on
September 25.
</P>
<P>
To encourage small-scale investors to apply, the government
will give them a 5.25-percent discount for the IPO, with loyalty
bonus shares to be issued in the ratio of 1:20 after one year and
1:15 after two years. Individual retail investors can get a
discount of 5.25 percent for the IPO.
</P>
<P>
Tsang described the privatization of the MTR as a "milestone"
since it will benefit the economy of Hong Kong and help enhance
Hong Kong's status as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of the MTR will reinforce the government's
commitment to a free market and bring about further improvements
in efficiency, productivity and flexibility of the MTR, he said.
</P>
<P>
The share offer of the MTR, the first for a major public asset
in Hong Kong, also sets the precedent for possible privatization
of other public of enterprises, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The listing of the MTR on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange will add
quality and diversity to the stock market. Besides, it would
generate considerable revenue for the government and help the
government "reduce or even avoid budget deficit," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The MTR was set up in 1975 as an enterprise solely owned by the
government. Over the past 25 years, the MTR has developed into an
efficient and mature mass transit system.
</P>
<P>
Tsang announced in his 1999 budget speech the government's
intention to privatize the MTR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Current Asian Depreciation Not to Trigger Another Crisis: Credit Suisse Economist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The situation was more serious in the Philippines. The
government's inability to reduce its fiscal deficit diminished the
confidence not only among international investors, but also among
the domestic retail people. Significant domestic capital has been
seen shifting out of pesos into U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
There are also concerns of the military actions in the
Philippines, which could further hammer the investors' confidence
as well as weaken the government fiscal position.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, the government also adopted weak baht policies,
hoping that by doing this it could substantially increase exports,
which provide better earnings for farmers.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we haven't seen a significant improvement in corporate
governance, we haven't seen the banking sector being properly
restructured and we haven't seen the mentality changing so
significantly," Tao cautioned.
</P>
<P>
This does not mean that Asia can not boom again, but this
certainly sets seat for a deja vu in 20 years down the road "
Structural weakness remains unchanged while economies are quickly
moving away from crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The currency-troubled countries in Asia still have quite a long
way to go, the economist said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia needs to generate a surplus accounting for 6 percent
of its GDP compared with the current 3 percent in deficit and it
has to do this in less than 10 years before they can get back to a
healthy fiscal stance, but 10 years of continuous efforts of this
target is extremely difficult. "This just highlights the hard task
ahead of the troubled countries," Tao emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Of course, even among the currency-troubled countries, they are
not facing exactly the same problems. For example, Thailand has a
much better fiscal position than the other two, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If there is not a substantial change in the current economic
policies, particularly the tax policies, and if the new government
can push forward the reforms of the banking sector, I do see
Thailand has a better chance to escape from the current severe
difficulties, much sooner than the other two countries," Tao
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Current Asian Depreciation Not to Trigger Another Crisis: Credit Suisse Economist (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A Credit Suisse economist
said Monday that the new round of currency depreciation in some
Southeast Asian countries will not trigger another crisis in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals between now and three or four years ago are
completely different," Hong Kong-based senior economist Dong Tao
noted in an interview with Xinhua. "The trends of weakened
regional currencies are all triggered by domestic political
factors and we are not seeing any major pan-regional kind of
economic fundamental weaknesses."
</P>
<P>
Compared with the situation in 1997, Tao, director and senior
regional economist of Credit Suisse First Boston (Hong Kong)
Limited, said the 1997 crisis was featured by regionally-driven,
pan-regional structural weaknesses while today's is a specific
politically-motivated currency weakness.
</P>
<P>
"We saw in 1997 tremendous over-investment, massive currency
deficit, artificial intervention by the central bank and more
underlined economic fundamentals, but for the time being, we have
not seen this kind of pan-regional structural weakness," Tao said.
</P>
<P>
And in fact, Tao noted, Southeast Asian countries, such as
Singapore and Malaysia, have recovered recently quite well, and "
this gives us the confidence: The new currency falls in the region
are more individual cases rather than a regional thing."
</P>
<P>
A recent research by Credit Suisse's analysts showed that the
currencies were quite weak but the key issue is the countries' own
main political factors and the related domestic capital outflows,
instead of pan-regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
There has been recently a significant depreciation of the
Indonesian rupiah, the Philippine peso and the Thai baht. Lately,
the rupiah saw some rebound, but in general the currency rate is
still quite low.
</P>
<P>
In April, Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid removed two of
his cabinet members, resulting in the country's political
instability and pushing Indonesia's currency close to 10,000
rupiah a U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In early August, some stability was seen returned, but
political uncertainties still remain and the cabinet still lacks
coherence. "We do think the currency will remain quite weak in the
coming months," Tao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
