<HEADLINE> Iran Hails Resumption of Relations With Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi here on Monday praised his country's
recent resumption of diplomatic relations with Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Hailing it as a great achievement of the Iranian government,
Asefi said the resumption of the relations would definitely be in
line with the mutual interests of both countries, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that Iran's reestablishment of ties with Algeria,
after a break of seven years, could break the ground for
enhancement of ties with other North African states.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and his Algerian counterpart
Abdelaziz Bouteflika announced on Friday that the two countries
would resume full diplomatic relations at the ambassadorial level
as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made in New York on the sidelines of the
United Nations millenium summit after the two leaders held "very
positive and fruitful" negotiations, Asefi said, adding that the
preparations for the resumption of ties had been made several
months ago at the request of Algerian officials.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman termed Iran and Algeria as two effective members
of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) as well as the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The two countries play a key role in the activities of the OIC
and OPEC with their active cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted the two countries' bilateral cooperation in
international organizations such as the Group 77 and the Non-
Aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Algeria broke off ties in 1993 after Algiers accused
Tehran of supporting the Islamic Salvation Front, the major
opposition of the Algerian government, a charge denied by Tehran.
</P>
</TEXT>
