<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Decision to Increase Oil Output "Wrong": Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tareq Aziz said Monday that it is wrong for the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to make the decision to
increase oil output by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
"We think the decision is wrong and the market does not actually
need such an increase," Aziz said in a televised interview,
referring to the agreement by the OPEC oil ministerial meeting on
Sunday to increase oil production by 800,000 barrels a day starting
from October in the face of soaring prices in world market.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the decision violated the OPEC agreement stipulating
that when oil prices go over a certain figure, the OPEC will
increase production by half million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
"Our analysis of the situation is that the core of the matter is
not shortage of fuel in the market, but the taxes imposed (on fuel)
by the United States and the Western governments," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz criticized that these governments do not want to lower the
taxes, but turn to press the oil-producing countries to increase
output to lower the surging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly declared its stance of opposing OPEC oil
production increase.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released last Thursday, Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Muhammad Rashid said, "All facts have confirmed that the quantity
of oil is sufficient in meeting the world demand."
</P>
<P>
Iraq had been part of the OPEC quota system until the 1991 Gulf
War, triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. Its oil
output has since been monitored by the United Nations, which
imposed sweeping sanctions on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
OPEC, the world's largest oil cartel, has increased its oil
output by 2.4 million barrels a day this year.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices hit a ten-year record high of 32.85 U.S. dollars a
barrel last Monday, while benchmark Brent crude for October was
traded at a new high of 32.88 dollars last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the European Union have been pressuring OPEC in
raising oil production to lower the oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
