<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Proposes "Functional Autonomy" Over Holy Site to Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami proposed on Monday to give the
Palestinians "functional autonomy" over the Temple Mount in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Ben-Ami said this would
give "symbolic expression" to the Palestinians desire for
sovereignty over the area, paving the way for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that "there can not be joint sovereignty" over
the holy site.
</P>
<P>
Israel would not be prepared to give up sovereignty over
Jerusalem and the holy places to Judaism, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem issue was the main stumbling block for the two
sides to reach a peace agreement, which had been scheduled for
September.
</P>
<P>
The flashpoint of negotiations was the walled compound in
Jerusalem's Old City. Known to Jews as the Temple Mount, it is the
site of their biblical Temples. To Muslims it is Haram Al-Sharif,
or Noble Sanctuary, with two mosques marking the spot where the
Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak suggested on Sunday in New
York where he was attending the United Nations Millennium Summit
that he was willing to consider less than full Israeli sovereignty
over the site, provided it was not handed to sole Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who insisted on Palestinian
sovereignty over the holy site, told U.S. President Bill Clinton in
New York last week that he would accept Islamic sovereignty there,
under the auspices of several Arab nations such as Jordan, Egypt,
Saudi Arabia and Morocco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
