<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 29 Al-Ma'unah Members Charged in High Court in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The 29 members of the Al-
Ma'unah deviate group accused of waging war against the Yang di-
Pertuan Agong (King) were Monday charged in the High Court here.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution will show that they intended to cause the
overthrow of the Government by unlawful means, Attorney-General
Mohtar Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
He told the court that "The accused persons had through the
communication set in their possession called on military personnel
to join them in their cause."
</P>
<P>
The 29 men claimed trial when the charge was read to them again
Monday. The charge is under Section 121 of the Penal Code which
provides for the death sentence or life imprisonment if found
guilty.
</P>
<P>
The 29 men are represented by a total of 32 lawyers while the
prosecution team is led by Mohtar.
</P>
<P>
The case, conducted before Justice Zulkefli Ahmad Makinudin,
has been classified as a security case and will be conducted in
accordance with the Essential (Security Cases) Regulation 1975.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Karpal Singh, representing Mohamad Amin, chief of the Al-
Ma'unah group in Malaysia, opposed the use of the security case
regulation, especially with regard to appeal.
</P>
<P>
However the judge did not make any ruling on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The 29 include 27 who surrendered to the security forces on
July 6 after their Bukit Jenalik base in Sauk in the northern
state of Perak was cordoned by the security forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
