<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Lay First Submarine Cable for Boosting Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA. September 11 (Xinhua -- Bangladesh is joining the global
club of high-speed submarine and cost-effective optical fiber
cable, breaking the barrier of cross-border communication, sources
in the Bangladesh Telegraph and Telephone Board(BTTB) said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The BTTB has signed recently a memorandum of understanding with
Tyco Submarine System Ltd. to roll out a submarine cable.
Southeastern port city Chittagong in Bangladesh and Tuas in
Singapore will be the landing points of this 3,213-kilometer
undersea cable, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Its initial capacity will be 40 gigabits-per-second(Gbps),
which could be expanded to 640 Gbps by using dense wave length
division multiplexing technology.
</P>
<P>
The cable-laying work, at a cost of 145 million U.S. dollars,
will start at the end of this year and be finished by early 2002.
A consortium of 40 carriers invested one billion dollars in this
venture.
</P>
<P>
The link will connect Bangladesh with the second Asia Pacific
Cable Network(APCN-2) to be operational from September, 2001,
which will link Japan, Korea, China, Hong Kong, the Philippines,
Malaysia and Singapore together.
</P>
<P>
Direct access to APCN-2 will relieve the BTTB and all private
telecommunication operators from struggling with the over-
congested international call traffic.
</P>
<P>
By fueling competition in the telecom market and revolutionize
the long-distance call market, the submarine cable will also
rescue the BTTB from revenue shrinkage, which is caused by high
rate of call piracy, overwhelming popularity of internet telephony
and illegal calls via leased satellite circuits, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC IT Conference Concludes in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The three-day SAARC
conference on Information Technology (IT) concluded here Monday
with participants calling for more regional cooperation to promote
IT development and application.
</P>
<P>
The participants suggested that all SAARC (South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation) member countries should take
country-level initiatives to promote IT for regional social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
They recommended seven areas for regional cooperation,
including sharing experiences in IT applications such as E-
governance, E-education, E-business and tele-medicine and
exploring the possibility of establishing a regional Internet
backbone to meet the growing requirements in IT-related fields.
</P>
<P>
About 150 governmental officials, tech minds and business
executives from all SAARC countries (except Maldives) and
observers from Singapore, Britain, Malaysia and Japan attended the
conference co-organized by SAARC secretariat and Nepali Ministry
of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Nepal, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, India, Pakistan,
Bhutan and Maldives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
