<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Output Increase Not Sufficient: Indian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- India expressed its
dissatisfaction Monday over the decision by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) on Sunday to increase crude
oil production by 800,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum and Natural Gas Minister Ram Naik told All India
radio that the increase should have been around 1.1 million
barrels a day to keep oil prices under control.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the OPEC move to increase output though I would have
been happy if the increase had been by about 1.05 million to 1.1
million barrels per day," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the announcement of OPEC decision in Vienna, Naik
said in a statement last night that he welcomed the decision but
expressed his hope that the increase, which is three percent of
the present OPEC production quota, would have "a salutary and
lasting effect on international oil prices".
</P>
<P>
Indian economy, especially aviation and land transports, were
hit hard due to the increase of oil prices in the international
markets.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether India would consider increasing oil prices in the
wake of increase in oil pool deficit, the Indian minister said the
government would consider all options including reduction in
excise and customs duty or issue of oil bonds to oil companies in
lieu of their arrears as well as mulling hike in oil prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
