<HEADLINE> Sensex Up on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sensitive Index (Sensex)
rose on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) Monday on late selling
triggered by reports of hike in prices of petroleum products by
the month-end.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-30 share Sensitive Index opened firm at 4,715.30 and
rose to the day's high of 4,748.81 at around mid-session. It later
reacted negatively reflecting the downslide and closed below the 4,
700-mark at 4,696.60 as against last Friday's close of 4,668.27,
still showing a net gain of 28.33 points.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index also improved further by 9.22 points to 2,399.
58 from the previous close of 2,390.36.
</P>
<P>
However, a statement by petroleum Minister Ram Naik that prices
of petroleum products would be hiked after Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee's return from the U.S. induced heavy selling
pressure from Foreign Institutional Investors as well as bull
liquidation. 
