<HEADLINE> Number of Illiterate in Indonesia Down to 6.9 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- There are still 6.9 million
illiterate people (from 10 to 44 years old) in Indonesia, an
official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Machmuri Muchlas, Director General of the Education Ministry
said at a press conference marking the International Illiteracy
Day that the government has successfully reduced the number of the
illiterate from 31.4 million in 1971 to 6.9 million this year.
</P>
<P>
"The government will keep hammering out plans for the coming
five years to deal with the illiteracy in the country," Muchlas
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Bureau of Statistic BPS), the number
of the illiterate in the country in 1980 reached over 30 million
and decreased in 1990 to 21.4 million and again in 1995 to 20
million.
</P>
<P>
The International Illiteracy Day, which falls on September 8
every year, was first cerebrated in 1967 after education ministers
from the United Nations Economic Social and Cultural Organization(
UNESCO) countries met in Iran in 1965. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
