<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Team Gives up Tests after Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan team on Monday gave up
Formula One tests at the Italian circuit of Mugello this week
because the fatal first-lap crash at the Italian Grand Prix left
without short of cars.
</P>
<P>
Two of the British team's cars were badly damaged in Sunday's
crash. In addition, the Italian prosecutor investigating the crash
has impounded the vehicles, along with other cars from other teams
involved in the smash-up.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was the only team forced to cancel tests for the next
championship race at Indianapolis on September 24. It had planned
to have drivers Heinz-Harald Frentzen and Jarno Trulli start
testing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Monza prosecutor Salvatore Bellomo, meanwhile, ordered an
inspection of the crash site - the Roggia corner - and an autopsy
on 33-year-old track worker Paolo Ghislimberti, who was killed by
flying debris.
</P>
<P>
Bellomo has already questioned drivers from Jordan, Ferrari,
McLaren-Mercedes and Arrows who were involved in the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
