<HEADLINE> Philippine Leader Alerts Armed Forces to Entry of Kidnappers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada ordered the country's armed forces on Monday to be on the
alert and prevent the entry into Philippine territory of a kidnap
group believed responsible for a new abduction near the Malaysian
island resort of Sipadan.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora and chief of the Military
Intelligence Service General Jose Calimlim announced the president
's directive at the presidential palace after a joint meeting of
the Mindanao Coordinating Council (MCC).
</P>
<P>
Calimlim said initial intelligence reports indicated that three
Malaysians were abducted either Sunday afternoon or early Sunday
evening on Padanan Island near Malaysia's Sipadan resort where 21
western tourists and Filipinos had been kidnapped in April.
</P>
<P>
Of the 21 Sipadan hostages taken by the Abu Sayyaf to their
jungle hideout in Jolo, Sulu, only one Filipino, Roland Ullah,
remains in captivity. The Abu Sayyaf had released the 20 original
hostages,including one Filipino.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said President Estrada issued his alert order after
receiving reports from the intelligence community on the new
abduction in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Upon instructions of the president, we have called the
Philippine Navy. We have also gotten in touch with the Philippine
Coastguard,"Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
"We have warned the authorities in Sulu and Basilan," he added,
"that if there are any unusual movements, they should take note
and do everything to prevent these kidnap victims from being
brought into the Philippines."
</P>
<P>
Calimlim said the Philippine Air Force has also been directed
to conduct flyovers in the border between the Philippines and
Malaysia and to closely monitor movements of boats that could be
carrying the kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
He said no details were given by Malaysian intelligence as to
the identities of the kidnappers or if they have any links with
the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Padanan is only half-an-hour by speedboat to the Philippines'
southernmost island of Tawi-Tawi, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
