<HEADLINE> Former Indonesian President May Refuse to Attend 2nd Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Three days ahead of the
second hearing of a case against Indonesia's former President
Soeharto, a lawyer of the defendant, Mohammad Assegaf, insisted
here Monday that his client was still not fit to appear before the
court.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Soeharto is still not in a good shape to appear in the
court.He still has a big problem in his communication skills," he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But, he indicated that his client could be tried "in absentia"
if in fact there is a permanent obstacle hampering the former
president from attending the trial.
</P>
<P>
"But the National Supreme Court firstly should issue an
instruction or an advice stipulating such a thing. As long as
there is no instruction from the Supreme Court, the South Jakarta
District Court, which is in charge of trying Soeharto, can not
stage 'in absentia trial' against Soeharto," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The district court should give more time and wait until the
defendant is really fit to appear before the court," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Because based on the country's crime code, the sick can not be
tried," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 79-year-old man, who ran the country for more than three
decades with an iron hand, failed to attend the trial on August 31
due to his bad health condition. He was reportedly not in a good
shape at that time after a series of strokes after stepping down
from the presidential office two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto faces charges of stealing 570 million U.S. dollars
from the state by funneling money from the tax-free charity
foundations he ran into the businesses of his family and friends.
</P>
<P>
Chief judge Lalu Mariyun adjourned the hearing until September
14,during which Soeharto's medical team along with an independent
medical team of the attorney general's office, were set to explain
the real health condition of the former ruler to the judges.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid has indicated that the trial
process should go on despite the absence of the former president
in the first hearing.
</P>
<P>
But so far it is not clear whether Soeharto could attend the
next trial or will keep being absent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
