<HEADLINE> Shuttler Drain on Rise in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian badminton
officials have been told to pay attention to the current trend of
athletes migrating to other countries and areas and carefully
consider both the negative and positive aspects of the trend.
</P>
<P>
"Countries (and areas) like Australia, Hong Kong, Japan,
Singapore and Chinese Taipei are interested in recruiting
Indonesian shuttlers," said Ciputra, patron of Jaya Raya badminton
club.
</P>
<P>
"It is good news as we can export qualified and skilled human
resources when it's difficult to find a job here. It's also an
opportunity to promote the sport in other countries," he was
quoted by the Jakarta Post Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ciputra, a construction tycoon, said it also gave coaches an
opportunity to work abroad with foreign clubs.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, we will have a shortage of players and some
of our teammates will become our opponents. We have to consider it
wisely whether athletes migrating will have a good or bad effect,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Mia Audina was naturalized after staying for eight
months in the Netherlands, where she moved with her Dutch-citizen
husband. Fung Permadi moved to Taipei more than five years ago
after failing to outperform national shuttlers. He has kept his
nationality. 
</P>
