<HEADLINE> IOC Believes Olympic Games Could be Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) revealed its belief on Sydney authorities on
Monday, saying that it can handle any protests during the games.
</P>
<P>
Francois Carrard, the IOC's director-general, said Sydney had
assured IOC members during a meeting on Monday about security.
</P>
<P>
"We got confirmation during the report by SOCOG (Sydney's
organising committee) that demonstrations would be handled
properly, in accordance with the law," Carrard said.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports, at least eight people, including
five police, were injured in clashes involving anti-globalisation
protesters around the gathering of business leaders who are in
Melbourne for the World Economic Forum meeting.
</P>
<P>
Police have said they expect at least some members of the loose
alliance of protesters to move on from the forum to the Olympics,
which open in Sydney on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Aborigine groups also plan to use the focus of the world
spotlight on the games to draw attention to their demands for
better treatment for indigenous Australians. 
