<HEADLINE> Athletes Face Night Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Athletes competing at the
Sydney Olympic Games could be selected to take out-of-competition
drug tests as late as the evening before their events, a leading
anti-doping official of the International Olympic Committee (IOC)
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
IOC has introduced a new test for the stamina-boosting
erythropoietin (EPO) and is also testing competitors for the first
time before their events at the Games for other drugs like
steroids.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to test the athletes on the day (of the start
of their events) but we will test athletes up to the evening prior
to the day of competition," IOC medical commission chief Patrick
Schamasch said.
</P>
<P>
Medal winners are also usually tested after their competitions
and random tests are normally carried out on other athletes who do
not finish in the top three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
