<HEADLINE> Seven Candidates Compete for Two Places on IOC Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Seven to two, this could mean
a fierce contest when seven candidates compete for two seats on
the International Olympic Committee's ruling executive board.
</P>
<P>
The names announced by Monday's deadline were: Vitaly Smirnov
of Russia, Franco Carraro of Italy, Lambis Nikolaou of Greece, Sam
Ramsamy of South Africa, Patrick Hickey of Ireland, Gunilla
Lindberg of Sweden and Guy Drut of France.
</P>
<P>
Lindberg, head of Sweden's national Olympic committee, is
considered likely to win one of the seats in Wednesday's election.
The IOC is eager to put another woman on the board to join Anita
DeFrantz of the United States.
</P>
<P>
An additional four seats on the board are to be filled as the
executive expands from 11 to 15 members.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's Denis Oswald, head of the international rowing
federation, is the only candidate for the spot reserved for the
summer sports bodies, while Mexico's Mario Vazquez Rana is the
sole candidate of the national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Ottavio Cinquanta, president of the international
skating union, has put his name forward as the candidate of the
winter sports federations. But that still has to be confirmed at a
September 22 meeting of the winter sports association.
</P>
<P>
A spot on the board has also been reserved for an active
athlete. That member will be decided by a vote of athletes on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany's Thomas Bach and Japan's Chiharu Igaya
will vye for the seat of IOC vice president being vacated by
Canada's Dick Pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
