<HEADLINE> Chinese Treasuries Down on Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China's T-bond market
slackened further as the bullish stock market and news of an IPO
drained capital away from fixed-income treasuries. Declines
outnumbered advances by a dominant five to one.
</P>
<P>
The transaction value on treasuries totaled 999 million yuan,
549 million yuan less than last Friday, according to Homeway,
China's leading financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
The new floating-rate ten-year 010004, whose interest rate is 2.
87 percent this year, led the decline by plummeting 0.56 percent
to end at 103.22 yuan, driving the yield up to 2.56 percent, from
2.49 percent on last Friday.
</P>
<P>
000896 (8.56 percent, due 2006) fell by 0.15 percent to 123.16
yuan, pushing the yield up 0.06 percentage points to 3.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both 000696 (11.83 percent, due 2006) and 0009908 (3.30 percent,
due 2009) tumbled by 0.13 percent, which has been translated into
a gain of about 0.03 percentage points in their yields.
</P>
<P>
009905 (3.28 percent, due 2007) was the only gainer, by edging
up 0.02 percent to the face value 100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's repo market saw a tame boom with a broad pickup in the
repurchasing prices. Combined trade volume of three-day, seven-day,
14-day and 28-day repurchasing transactions was 7.76 billion yuan,
down 119 million yuan from the previous trading day. The interest
rate of the three-day repurchasing agreement rose from 2.4 percent
to 3.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
