<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Wants Permanent Solution to E. Timorese Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
expected to find a permanent solution to problems arising from the
continued presence of East Timorese refugees in East Tenggara
Province, a senior official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia does not want to be blamed all the time for every
case emerging (due to the presence of) the refugees and the
militias," Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and
Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono said after meeting with
President Abdurrahman Wahid at the Merdeka Palace.
</P>
<P>
President Wahid met with key officials including Vice President
Megawati Soekarnoputri, Yudhoyono, Defense Force chief Adm. Widodo
AS, Police chief Gen. Rusdinhardjo and Coordinating Minister for
Economic Affairs Rizal Ramli a few hours after returning Monday
morning from his trip to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Yudhoyono said that what is happening to the East Timorese
refugees at present is similar to what had happened to them while
fleeing East Timor last year.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a joint cooperation to solve the problems and
Indonesia will not put itself again in a position where it could
be blamed for anything that could happen to the refugees or the
militias," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will make proposals on how to solve the
refugees issue to the U.N. Transitional Administration in East
Timor (UNTAET) and the East Timorese Resistance Council.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Indonesia will propose the promotion
of the existing cooperation on the border between East Timor and
East Nusa Tenggara by establishing a joint patrol and exchanging
liaison officers between Indonesia and UNTAET.
</P>
<P>
"Under the framework of the joint border committee, we will
discuss further what methodology will be used by the Indonesian
military at the border areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that Indonesia hopes this could be
implemented soon to ensure that the country could monitor and
control the activities of East Timorese refugees, militias or the
local people in the border.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the killing of three U.N. aid workers in Atambua,
East Nusa Tenggara, last Wednesday, Yudhoyono said the government
is still awaiting the report of the team formed to investigate the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The incident broke out after hundreds of pro-Jakarta militia
and refugees attacked and burned the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees in Atambua following the murder of
former pro-integration fighter Olivio Mendoza Moruk.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has unanimously called on Indonesia
to take immediate steps to disarm and disband the militia in
Indonesia responsible for the killing of the U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
Yudhoyono said Indonesia will make a comprehensive response to
the U.N. resolution urging the country to disarm and disband the
militia.
</P>
<P>
Atambua was the center for international relief efforts for
more than 120,000 East Timorese still living in refugee camps
across the border after their homeland voted a year ago to break
away from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has closed its operations in East Nusa
Tenggara after the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects in East Timor Mayhem Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Three of the 19 prospective
suspects in an alleged human rights abuse case in East Timor were
grilled on Monday at the Indonesian Attorney General's Office here.
</P>
<P>
Let. Col. Yayat Sudrajat, former commander of the Tribuana
Military Task Force in East Timor; Col. Nur Muis, former commander
of the Dily Resort Military Command; and Herman Sudiyono, former
regent of Cova Lima were questioned Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The investigators also questioned two witnesses, namely Col.
Mudjiono, former deputy chief of the Dily Resort Military Command,
and Muafi Sawidi, former deputy police chief of Dili, capital of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
After the questioning, Yayat Sudrajat declined to comment on
the result of Monday's investigation, saying, "I have done my
duties. What I did (in East Timor) was what I had to do at that
moment."
</P>
<P>
In early September, chief of the investigation team into
serious human rights offenses in East Timor, M.A. Rachman,
announced as many as 19 civilians and military personnel as
prospective suspects in the human rights abuse case in the
breakaway province of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The rights violations took place after the territory voted in
favor of independence in August last year in a U.N.-sponsored
direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, who was chief of the country's armed forces at that
time, was not included in the list of suspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
