<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Moves to Enlarge ASEAN Swap Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan has called a meeting
with the six founding members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) and China and South Korea to discuss
bilateral swap fund arrangements, the Thai News Agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor of the Central Bank of Thailand Pakornmalakul
Nayudh was quoted as saying in Brunei that if Japan's meeting with
the six ASEAN founders, including Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore and Thailand, as well as China and South
Korea led to smooth conclusions, the total credit line of the
expanded ASEAN swap fund arrangements would be larger.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN members agreed to increase the ASEAN Swap Fund to 1
billion U.S. dollars from 200 million dollars at a meeting of
ASEAN central bankers held in Brunei last month.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Swap Fund is part of the Asian Monetary Fund (AMF), a
currency safety net accord reached by finance ministers of the
five ASEAN founders plus China, Japan and South Korea at the
annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank in Thailand's
northern resort province of Chiang Mai in May.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the accord, known as the Chiang Mai
Initiative, is to enable a country short of foreign reserves to
borrow from others in the agreed network to absorb and address
unjustified selling pressure on its currency by speculators
without having to devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
Japan already has swap agreements with South Korea and Malaysia,
worth 5 billion dollars and 2.5 billion dollars respectively and
is planning to conclude a similar accord with Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a recent announcement that progress has been
seen in the AMF initiative, as finance ministers of the ASEAN
founders and their counterparts from the three key Asian economies
were actively examining technical details of a web of central bank
swap lines and repurchase agreements, aiming to unveil an initial
blueprint of the AMF by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Pakornmalakul spoke of the issue on the sidelines of a meeting
of finance ministers and central bankers of member economies of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, being held in Brunei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
