<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fine Weather Waits for Olympic Opening Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sydney Olympic Games could
be opened in fine weather on Friday, weather forecasters said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meteorology Bureau spokesman Kevin O'Loughlin, giving the
first official forecast for the period covering the Opening
Ceremony for the games, meanwhile also said that Sydney's spring
weather could produce surprises.
</P>
<P>
"We rely mainly on climatology, our computer models run out
only to about seven days, so climatologically it still looks
fairly favourable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However in September we get some rain usually one day in
three on a statistical average."
</P>
<P>
The forecast minimum temperature is 11 Celsius (51.8 degrees
Fahrenheit) in the morning, with a maximum of 21 Celsius (69.8
degrees Fahrenheit) in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
O'Loughlin said he would be surprised if there was a repeat of
the strong winds that have hit Sydney in recent days.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "We couldn't rule that out because it's spring
time and it's a changeable time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
