<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Near Daya Bay Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The red tide that heavily
damaged marine life in waters in Daya Bay off south China's
Guangdong Province since early September disappeared today.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the State Oceanic Administration's Nanhai Branch
said, the red tide was first spotted in waters near Aotou Town in
Huizhou City on September 3, and expanded to 30 square kilometers
on September 7. It started to break up last Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to specialists with the Nanhai Branch, the red tide
was mainly caused by industrial waste water and sewage discharged
into Daya Bay.
</P>
<P>
The red tide had caused about five million yuan in economic
losses to local farmers who cultivated aquatic products in sunken
nets in the offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
Due to efforts of local departments to monitor and control red
tide development in the offshore areas, the red tide did not have
much negative impact on offshore aquaculture in the county.
</P>
<P>
Another red tide occurred in mid-August in the same sea area
causing severe economic losses to local aquatic product farmers.
</P>
<P>
However, experts with the Nanhai Branch have requested
departments concerned to study the environments affected and stay
alert to red tides in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
