<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Palestinian Central Council, the Palestine Liberation
Organization's decision-making body, Sunday decided to postpone
declaring statehood for at least two months, but gave the go-ahead
to launch preparations for future sovereignty, such as possibly
expanding the Palestinian Police.
</P>
<P>
Ending a two-day meeting in Gaza City, the 129-member Council
put the PLO's Executive Committee, headed by Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, in charge of setting a date to declare a state
sometime between November 15 and January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
In New York, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's spokesman
called the move "a positive step."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said during a tour of
Hebron Sunday that the settlers there bear more responsibility than
the city's Palestinians for the violent incidents that have erupted
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after he was briefed by Central Command
officers, Sneh said, "To my regret, from what I've learned it is in
fact certain elements within the (Jewish) community who have
increased the number of violent acts."
</P>
<P>
He added that he wished to avoid generalizations and that he was
speaking of "a few people within the community - either they or
their children who have been educated in a certain manner."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Senior police officers met Sunday with supporters of former
Shas party leader and interior minister Aryeh Deri, who began his
prison service for bribe-taking on September 3.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami has agreed to
a request by the Prisons Service to allow only one Knesset
(parliament) member a week to visit Deri.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Ehud Barak, addressing Jewish leaders Sunday,
declared his absolute commitment to what he pointedly called his "
civil agenda," which analysts believe will separate religion from
the state.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he could not accept the current situation in which
couples unable to marry under Orthodox Jewish decree are forced to
flee to abroad to wed.
</P>
<P>
He added that there were 1 million immigrants from the former
Soviet Union now in Israel without private cars and unable to
travel to beaches or other recreational areas because of the ban on
the public transportation system on Shabbat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
