<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary September 11 Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary Monday, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's sheep production annually contributes
about 25 billion rupees (about 470 million U.S. dollars) to the
country's economy, Associated Press of Pakistan reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The country's sheep industry produces about 300,000 tons of
meat and 50,000 tons of wool each year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
XIAMEN -- China welcomes foreign businessmen to invest in the
country's information, machinery, light and petrochemical
industries, to help reform and cooperate with Chinese enterprises
in these fields, spokesmen for the industries said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They made these remarks while briefing representatives of
multinational corporations, who are attending the on-going fourth
China Fair for International Investment and Trade, on related
policies and situations.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
XIAMEN -- Foreign businessmen are welcome to invest in the west-
east gas transmission projects and are permitted to have a
controlling share in such projects, said an official with the
State Council Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Ai, from the developing western region office, told
representatives of multinational corporations that this was one of
China's special policies encouraging the inflow of foreign funds
into the western region.
</P>
<P>
Another special policy, Zhao said, will allow the involvement
of foreign investors in the construction of urban gas pipeline
networks.
</P>
<P>
The official said foreign businessmen, who invest in the west-
east gas transmission projects, will enjoy preferential policies
in terms of communication and energy resources, as well as other
preferential policies associated with the development of the
western region.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- A draft of amendments to year 2000 state budget
plans was approved by the new Mongolian government on Monday and
will be submitted to the State Great Hural (parliament), the Ulan
Bator Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government said the amendments reflect the
country's current economic and financial situation.
</P>
<P>
With the amendments, budget income will total 322 million U.S.
dollars, 7.6 million dollars more than the original budget's.
Expenditures will amount to 414 million dollars, 1.9 million
dollars less than the non-amended budget's.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's economy grew a real 1 percent in the April-
June quarter from the previous term for the second consecutive
quarterly increase, the Economic Planning Agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter growth in gross domestic product translates
into an annualized expansion of 4.2 percent, the agency said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
