<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Urges Restoration of International Confidence in ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- International confidence in
the Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) has not yet
been restored despite the region's quick recovery from the Asian
economic crisis, Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 21st General Assembly
of the ASEAN Inter-Parliamentary Organization (AIPO) here, Lee
said nagging negative perceptions about ASEAN remain as the crisis
had set back ASEAN's economic dynamism and raised doubts about its
credibility and relevance as a regional organization.
</P>
<P>
To restore confidence in ASEAN, he said, the grouping must
first convince international investors and dialogue partners with
serious adoptions of the best standards of government,
transparency, corporate governance and rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, ASEAN members must press on with cooperation
initiatives such as the ASEAN Free Trade Area and the ASEAN
Investment Area, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, ASEAN must also help its newer members catch up and
integrate with the region and the world economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The AIPO, founded 1977, comprises eight member countries --
Indonesia, Singapore, Malaysia, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam, the
Philippines and Cambodia. The two permanent observer countries are
Brunei and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Attending the assembly are 19 countries from AIPO, its two
permanent observer countries and nine observer nations including
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
