<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stocks End Lower on Rate Hike Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Share prices at the Philippine
Stock Exchange ended lower Monday amid fears of the impact of the
central bank's interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
The 30-company Phisix, the market's main index, fell 22.21
points to close at 1,501.48.
</P>
<P>
The broader all-shares index also shed 17.56 points to 679.86.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said domestic companies are concerned over the effect
of higher interest rates on the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The drop of the market is an immediate reaction to the central
bank's decision to raise the interest rate by one percentage point.
Companies
find it hard to cope with the situation," said Warren Chua,a local
marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank raised its key overnight rates by
one percentage point effective Monday, in anticipation of
inflationary pressures from a weak peso and higher petroleum
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
