<HEADLINE> Anti-terrorism Bill to be Tabled by Ugandan Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has revealed that the Cabinet is soon to table an anti-
terrorism bill under which all persons captured in action against
the government will be charged and punished severely.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from the President's Office
available on Monday, the president said that the government has
been very lenient with criminals, which has greatly undermined the
peace and stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Once the bill becomes law, people convicted of waging war
against the state will be severely punished to serve as an example
to all enemies of democracy," Museveni was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The president, who was on a fact-finding visit to Mubende
district in western Uganda Saturday over the recent rebel invasion,
said that those involved in such activities are bankrupt
politicians trying to reverse the democratization process in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He called on Ugandans to be on the lookout for such elements
and report them to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged the youth to join the local defense
forces to help strengthen security within their areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
