<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble in Tokyo on Nasdaq Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Monday, dampened by last Friday's decline in New York's technology-
heavy Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issue on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 370.65 points, or 2.25
percent from last Friday's close to end at 16,130.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 32.61 points or 2.16 percent to 1,477.
27.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 540.89 million
shares from last Friday's 907.11 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Continuing unwinding of corporate cross-shareholdings ahead of
the midyear book-closing this month was another factor leading
share prices lower, traders said.
</P>
<P>
High-tech issues were weak after the Nasdaq lost 119.94 points
to 3,978.41 last Friday, closing below 4,000 for the first time in
almost three weeks, while the food, telecom and retail sectors
also marked sharp declines.
</P>
<P>
The mining and marine transportation industries were the only
gainers among the 33 business sectors on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers overwhelmed
gainers 1,062 to 254, with 108 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
