<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Public Works and Housing Minister Koray Aydin said on
Saturday that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) granted Turkey
prestige among the states of the world.
</P>
<P>
Aydin said that the government was not acting upon the IMF's
pressure but giving services in accordance with its own decisions.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF has granted Turkey prestige among the world countries.
Turkey has been never rejected from the doors it resorted to," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is implementing a three-year economic stability program
supported by the IMF to drop its runaway inflation.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- The "Sorbet Royal-2000," a massive submarine escape and
rescue maneuver that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
launches once every three years, was continuing on Sunday, 40
nautical miles off the southern Turkish Mersin Gulf in the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Naval Forces is hosting the training exercise. The
United States Dallas submarine could not attend the exercise due to
a technical failure in its power system.
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- Hartmut Schrim, project director of the Pipeline Engineering
(PLE) company, said on Sunday that the Baku-Ceyhan Oil Pipeline
Project would not pass through forested areas or archaeological
sites.
</P>
<P>
The company will carry out the basic engineering work of the
project which will transfer rich Caspian oil to the western markets
via Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Yildirim Akbulut, speaker of the Grand National Assembly
(parliament) of Turkey, left for the Croatian capital Zagreb on
Sunday to attend the Parliament Speakers' Summit on "
Parliamentarians' Role in Implementation of Stability Pact and
Europe-Atlantic Integration."
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure, Akbulut said the issue of strengthening
inter-parliamentary cooperation among Southeast European countries
would be discussed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The four-day summit will start on September 12, attended by
parliament speakers of Turkey, Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Bulgaria, Greece, Italy, Hungary, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland,
Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Belgium, the Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, France,
Canada, Lithuania, Latvia, the Netherlands, Spain, Sweden and
Britain will be represented at the deputy premiership or
ministerial level. 
</P>
