<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Schools to File Lawsuit Against Education Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's private schools were
prepared to file a lawsuit against the Education Ministry for
refusing to renew the licences for 600 out of 1,130 private
schools of the kingdom, the semiofficial Jordan Times reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Private Schools Owners Syndicate said the ministry refused
to renew the licences for these schools on the account that they
failed to implement its directive to install computers for students
before the start of the current school semester on September 3.
</P>
<P>
The ministry had ordered all schools in the country to install
at least one computer for every 10 students by September 1, but
representatives of the syndicate met Education Minister Kliaijd
Touqan in August, who agreed to a more lenient three-year-plan for
private schools to install the computers, Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Licences for private schools in Jordan are temporary and renewed
each year following inspections by officials from the education
ministry to prove if they meet the criteria set by the ministry,
and the installation of computers were added to the criteria of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's new measure was part of its campaign to eradicate
computer illiteracy among students in the kingdom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
