<HEADLINE> Manila Confirms Kidnapping of Three Malaysians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government on
Monday confirmed that three Malaysians were kidnapped Sunday by
armed men believed to be Abu Sayyaf members off an island resort
in Malaysia's Sabah state.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora made the confirmation and
said the government has ordered navy soldiers to prevent the
kidnappers from entering the Philippine waters.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Monday that after the unidentified gunmen left the
resort in a speedboat, the three Malaysians were declared missing.
They added that the attackers were heading for Philippine waters.
</P>
<P>
Reports also noted that the kidnapping at Pasir Dive Resort on
Padanan Island off Sabah late Sunday night has been confirmed by
the local Malaysian police.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf group in the southern Philippines is suspected
to be behind the abduction.
</P>
<P>
Since the kidnapping site is about one hour's ride by speedboat
from the southernmost Philippine islands, other reports said the
new hostages might have been brought into Philippine territory.
</P>
<P>
More than four months ago, Abu Sayyaf rebels kidnapped 21
people,including 10 foreign tourists, from Malaysia's Sipadan
diving resort,also off Sabah. They were then taken to Jolo island
in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Although one Filipino is still held captive, yet nearly all the
hostages have since been freed. Earlier, the Philippine
authorities warned that the Abu Sayyaf rebels, who received
millions of dollars from negotiators, might return to Malaysian
waters again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
