<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Wheat Output Expected to Fall 60 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia National Farmers'
Union (ZNFU) has projected a decline of 60 percent in local wheat
production in the 2000/2001 farming season because of escalating
production costs and the proliferating of cheap imports, Times of
Zambia newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU President Ajay Vashee said in an interview in Ndola,
Copperbelt Province, on Sunday the number of local wheat producers
had continued to decrease in the last three years because of the
dwindling returns on the crop.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Vashee as saying Zambia was expected to
produce less than 60,000 tons of wheat this season, a figure which
was far less than 90,000 tons the country produced in the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
He said subsidized wheat imports which had flooded Zambia
discouraged the local farmers from fully engaging in the
production of the crop.
</P>
<P>
Vashee said the local wheat corp depended largely on irrigation
and as such, the cost of power and fuel to operate the equipment,
was too high compared to other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia's national consumption was 120,000 tons of wheat
per annum but because of the obtaining situation, it was not
possible for the farmers to meet the national demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Get More Funds to Fight Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is expected to get 450
million U.S. dollars from donors to ease problems arising from
drought-related revenue shortfalls, the East African weekly
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sum, equivalent to 4 percent of Kenya's gross domestic
product, is to be released in November.
</P>
<P>
Jose Fajgenbaum, senior advisor to the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for Africa, said the money is not targeted at any
specific area of the budget and the Kenyan government will have
the latitude to use it for "whatever priorities are deemed highest.
"
</P>
<P>
The relaxed conditions for the aid package are understood to
have been negotiated during a Washington lunch meeting last
Thursday between Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi and the IMF head
Horst Kohler, the weekly said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total sum, only 52 million dollars is coming directly
from the IMF in the form of a long-term loans at concessional
rates, pending final approval by the IMF's board meeting set for
October 18 this year.
</P>
<P>
Another portion of the package, amounting to around 160 million
dollars, will be in the form of the expected energy-related
assistance from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
An IMF mission concluded its nine-day visit to Kenya last week
for assessing additional aid necessitated by the drought in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
