<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bicommunal Festival of Mutual Understanding Held in Cyprus Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Greek and Turkish
Cypriots Sunday night gathered at the U.N.-controlled Ledra Palace
hotel in Nicosia to attend a "festival of mutual understanding."
</P>
<P>
The festival was organized by four Greek-Cypriot and three
Turkish- Cypriot parties under the auspices of the Slovak embassy
in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The political parties and the people who have come to the
festival are sending a clear message that they want peace, Slovak
ambassador Dusan Rozbora said, expressing the hope that more such
events will be held in the future.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Agriculture Minister Costas Themistocleous, who also
attended the festival, stressed the importance of such events as
they help build trust between the two divided communities of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Even if a settlement is found, without trust and mutual
understanding it cannot last," he said.
</P>
<P>
Demitris Christofias, general secretary of the left-wing AKEL
party, noted that such events "aim at doing away with the division
and bringing together the two communities of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
His words were echoed by Panayiotis Demetrou, deputy president
of right-wing ruling Democratic Rally party, who also said that "
mutual understanding is important even before a settlement is
achieved and especially after."
</P>
<P>
The president of the United Democrats party and former President
of Cyprus, George Vassiliou, also turned up for the event.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, General Secretary of the
Republic Turkish Party Ferdi Sabit Soyer described the event as "a
good step" and expressed the hope that more will follow.
</P>
<P>
President of the Turkish Cypriot Communal Liberation Party
Mustafa Akkinci said the festival sends the message that people
from both communities want peace.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the Mediterranean island after a failed coup in
Nicosia seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of United Nations-sponsored proximity talks have
been held, which aimed at paving the way for substantive
negotiations to reach a settlement in Cyprus. The fourth round will
open in New York on September 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
