<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Condemns Protesters of World Economic Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Premier Steve Bracks of
Australia's Victoria State Monday described protesters at the
World Economic Forum Summit as extremists, saying they were
responsible for the violence which occurred during the summit.
</P>
<P>
"Could I say that I condemn outright some of the protesters for
the action they have taken," he was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying. "It is not Australian -- it's very un-
Australian -- and it's obviously a matter which is of enormous
regret to me as premier of Victoria and I think most decent
Australians as well."
</P>
<P>
The premier warned that the protesters would face the full
force of the law.
</P>
<P>
Peaceful protesters were being drawn in by extremists, Bracks
said.
</P>
<P>
"We will take necessary force and action to ensure the
conference continues to go ahead and people also have the right to
peaceful protest as well," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a law approved last week by the Australian
Parliament, the armed forces could be called in to tackle civil
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Violence occurred Monday morning in Melbourne, where thousands
of protesters attempted to "shut down" the three-day World
Economic Forum's Asia Pacific Summit, which opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
The protesters claimed that the WEF is the club of the world's
rich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
