<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila's Intervention Calms Down Currency Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank
Governor Rafael Buenaventura said Monday that the government's
intervention in the foreign currency market has slightly beefed up
dollar circulation in the domestic front.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura said this in a statement issued here in a bid to
clarify reports that the central bank is not doing anything to
save the peso, the local currency.
</P>
<P>
He also contradicted earlier allegations that the central bank
had indeed released a large bulk of its reserves to contain the
further slide of the peso.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the central bank is doing its best to keep the
government's dollar reserve so as not to affect its import
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura also dismissed reports that the peso is the only
currency that depreciated in the region, noting that all the other
regional currencies have also depreciated.
</P>
<P>
At any rate, he expressed confidence that the foreign currency
market will improve because of increased dollar remittances from
overseas Filipino workers.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso was traded weaker against the U.S. dollar
early Monday amid fears that the central bank would again
intervene in the currency market.
</P>
<P>
The peso averaged 45.589 against the U.S. dollar Monday, weaker
than the previous close of 45.545. Dealers said the government's
intervention is expected to create an artificial stability in the
foreign exchange rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
