<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said Sunday that it welcomed a Palestinian
decision to delay the declaration of independent statehood until
at least November 15.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome this confirmation from the Palestinians of their
renewed commitment to pursue negotiations and the search for peace,
" British Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain, who is responsible
for Middle East affairs, said in a statement. "Both sides need to
make every effort in the coming weeks," he said. Hain's statement
was issued shortly after the 129-member Palestinian Central
Council (PCC) said Sunday after a meeting in Gaza that final
preparations for statehood should be completed by November 15. (
Britain-Palestine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- A special envoy of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) arrived here Monday for a four-day visit for talks to
further implement the South-North Joint Declarations signed this
June.
</P>
<P>
Kim Yong Sun, a special envoy of DPRK leader Kim Jong Il and
one of his closest confidants, flew into Seoul directly from
Pyongyang Monday morning. Kim, who is in charge of concrete inter-
Korean affairs, will meet with South Korean Unification Minister
Park Jae-kyu Monday afternoon to discuss inter-Korean issues,
especially the reconnection of the Seoul-Shinuiju Railroad,
government officials said. (SKorea-DPRK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Office goers encountered Monday morning what they
saw on Sunday television -- road blockades in downtown Brussels
disrupting returning traffic from weekend.
</P>
<P>
Between 600 and 700 heavy-duty trucks refused to leave even
though their planned come-and-go drive-by protest was already
prolonged by 12 hours till three o'clock on Monday morning. The
Sunday protest, organized by the Union of Professional Road
Transport of Belgium, drew more than 1,700 trucks from around the
country. They were joined by tourist coaches, taxis, school buses,
inter-city buses and motorbikes. (Belgium-Blockades-Traffic)
</P>
</TEXT>
