<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Record-holder Shi Zhiyong Quits Olympics Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Olympic gold medal
hopeful Shi Zhiyong, men's world record holder in the 62-kg class,
has to withdraw from the upcoming Olympic Games because of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
"He was forced to quit the Games for a injury just several days
before we left for Sydney last week," leader of the Chinese
weightlifting team Wei Di told Xinhua on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shi set the new world record of 152.5 kilograms in snatch at
the Asian Weightlifting Championships in May in Japan, breaking
his own mark of 147.5 kilograms created at the World Championships
November last year in Greece, where he won the gold medal for the
snatch and placed fourth for the total.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old had been considered one of the contenders for
the gold medal in his category, which will be held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Cui Wenhua, world champion in the 1997 World Championships for
the 108-kg class, also quit the Games due to feet injury. He was
originally to take part in the 105-kg event and hope to catch a
medal for China.
</P>
<P>
"Both of the lifters suffered injuries and have to give up the
Olympics," Wei said. "It's unlucky for the two who have prepared
for a long time with hard works." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uzbek Olympic Official Needs Banned Drug for Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- An Uzbekistan Olympic team
official, who was detained for carrying performance-enhancing
substances at Sydney airport last week, needed the drugs for an
illness, Uzbekistan's National Olympic Committee (NOC) president
Sabirjan Ruziev said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ruziev said Sergei Voynov, 45, needed the muscle-building
human growth hormone (HGH) for a skin disorder.
</P>
<P>
Since the incident last Thursday he has gone to a Sydney
hospital with cardiac problems.
</P>
<P>
"He has been ill since 1997. He needs it," Ruziev said."When
Mr Voynov got to the customs hall, he voluntarily went up to the
customs officer and said he had this drug.
</P>
<P>
"On September 7 and 8 customs officials questioned Mr Voynov.
On Friday evening his blood pressure increased alarmingly and he
complained of chest pains."
</P>
<P>
He added in a statement: "At 10 pm on September 8 he was taken
to Concord Hospital (in Sydney) where he is at the cardiac unit
undergoing tests."
</P>
<P>
Uzbek officials said, however, that they hoped Voynov would be
able to leave hospital later on Monday.
</P>
<P>
HGH can be used to help children with stunted growth but it is
believed to be abused by some athletes who want to boost their
power.
</P>
<P>
Under Australian law the maximum punishment for carrying it
illegally into the country is a fine of 100,000 Australian dollars
(56,000 U.S. dollars) or a five-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has yet to develop a test for HGH, an expensive
substance which is believed to be fashionable with cheats.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said the official's Olympic accreditation would be
withdrawn if the person was found to have smuggled illegal drugs
into Australia.
</P>
<P>
But Ruziev said: "It is important to stress that Mr Voynov was
not detained or even questioned but was allowed to proceed with
the team to the Olympic village." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to China Going Up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From January to July, foreign investment in the region
accounted for more than 10 percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China is now carrying out a strategic readjustment
of its economy, and encourages foreign businesses to participate
in the reform of state enterprises in various forms. China has
also taken a series of steps to encourage foreign investors to set
up research and development centers in China, and pour funds into
high-tech industries, which is in accordance with the global
development strategy of multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
Gregory C. Chow, an economist from the United States held that
the decrease of foreign investment in China is only a temporary
phenomenon. "China will still be an attraction for foreign funds
in the future with the improvement of both the domestic and
overseas environment."
</P>
<P>
China has taken the lead in absorbing foreign direct investment
in developing countries for seven years in row since 1993.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Businessmen are Speaking Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN September 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign
businessmen who can speak Chinese has increased rapidly in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
And it was quite an easy thing to find a foreigner who speaks
fluent Chinese at the fourth China Fair for International
Investment and Trade, which is being held in the port city of
Xiamen, southeast China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Miss Zhang, who has attended the fair for three consecutive
years, said that at the previous fairs, the earphones for
foreigners to hear simultaneous interpretation often fell short of
demand. However, she said, this year, many foreigners do not ask
for the earphones at all.
</P>
<P>
"They want to hear the original edition of Chinese policies,"
joked Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Hong Jun Park, a representative from Hyundai of the Republic of
Korea (ROK), is one of those foreign businessmen who did not ask
for an earphone at the fair.
</P>
<P>
Hong first studied Chinese in ROK. He said in ROK, more than 5,
000 students graduate from Chinese language departments each year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese is only second to English in popularity among foreign
languages in ROK following the establishment of diplomatic
relations between ROK and China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He thought it is more convenient if one can speak the language
of the country where he has businesses to do.
</P>
<P>
A representative from China General Electric Corp. said that GE
has more than 7,000 employees in China, and they usually speak
Chinese in the offices, adding "We attach great importance to the
localization."
</P>
<P>
Juergen D. Lagleder, senior vice-president of Siemens Ltd.,
China, said that 50 percent of his company's foreign employees can
speak Chinese.
</P>
<P>
He also wants to improve his Chinese speaking ability, and he
encourages his employees to learn Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Commentators said that speaking Chinese does not necessarily
imply that one can do good business in China. However, the fact
that more and more foreign businessmen are starting to learn
Chinese actually means that the Chinese market is attractive to
them.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that China will remain one of the biggest markets
in the world in the 21st century, since the country's economy has
made a turn for the better and its accession into the World Trade
Organization enters its final stage.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that up to now, more than 20,000
foreigners have attended training courses to learn commercial
Chinese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
