<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Govt Aids Research, Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
has allocated 11.8 million NZ dollars (about 5 million U.S.
dollars) to help private firms carry out research and development
programs.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the government here Monday said the
new fund is called Grants for Private Sector R&AMP;D and is managed by
the New Zealand Foundation for Research, Science and Technology.
Its aim is to increase the level of private sector R&AMP;D in New
Zealand by co-funding new research projects.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to build a true knowledge society in New
Zealand and research and innovation are essential to achieving
that," New Zealand Minister for Research, Science and Technology
pete Hodgson said in the press release.
</P>
<P>
"Private sector R&AMP;D in New Zealand is only about 0.34 percent
of GDP. This is very low by international standards and we need to
substantially increase business investment in R&AMP;D here.
</P>
<P>
"Wealth today is coming more from knowledge and ideas than from
the production of commodities. This means the talent and
experience New Zealanders have applied to primary production and
processing must be applied increasingly to research and
development. We have to convert the results of our academic and
industrial research into value-added exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new fund complements existing support for business offered
by the Foundation. Total funds in this respect are now 36 million
NZ dollars (over 15 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
