<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blockades Drag on to Disrupt Brussels Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Office goers encountered
Monday morning what they saw on Sunday television -- road
blockades in downtown Brussels disrupting returning traffic from
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Between 600 and 700 heavy-duty trucks refused to leave even
though their planned come-and-go drive-by protest was already
prolonged by 12 hours till three o'clock on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday protest, organized by the Union of Professional Road
Transport of Belgium, drew more than 1,700 trucks from around the
country. They were joined by tourist coaches, taxis, school buses,
inter-city buses and motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
Like their equivalents in France, Germany and Britain, the
truck drivers were protesting against the ever-rising fuel prices,
caused by both tight production quota of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and the government taxation
on fuels for revenue and environment reasons.
</P>
<P>
The union met the Belgian transport ministry officials Sunday
evening but failed to agree on anything. Another meeting was
scheduled for Monday morning and no one expects there will be any
result of that meeting in which European Union (EU) finance
ministers already expressed a "no change" of their policy on
taxing fuels.
</P>
<P>
The ministers during their weekend meeting at Versaille only
demanded the OPEC to increase production so as to reduce oil
prices. The OPEC in its turn decided on Sunday to raise its daily
production by 800,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Fuel prices, both petrol and diesel, rose by close to 20
percent in the last three years in Belgium. A liter of petrol now
costs around 48 Belgian francs (about 1.06 U.S. dollars) while a
liter of diesel costs around 35 francs (about 77 cents).
</P>
<P>
Belgian Budget Minister Johan Vande Lanotte estimated that the
rising prices of crude oil alone cost his country 15 billion
Belgian francs (about 33.3 million dollars) more this year and
that could mean a decrease of revenue next year in the amount of
25 billion francs (about 55.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The rocketing of oil prices posted since early 1999 has
triggered a debate in the EU on the crude oil prices, refining and
distribution as well as taxation on oil products, the three
components of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seem determined to fluctuate within a band
of 30 dollars a barrel and it entered that band in February this
year following an uninterrupted rise since December 1998 when the
crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
