<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorpe Among First Batch Tested for EPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian gold medal contender
Ian Thorpe was among the first of the country's athletes who were
called to be blood tested for the banned drug EPO on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe trained at the Sydney Olympic pool and then was taken
away by drug testing officials along with fellow swimmers Kieren
Perkins,Grant Hackett and Hayley Lewis.
</P>
<P>
Australian head swimming coach Don Talbot applauded the blood
testing program Monday, but joined five-time American Olympic swim
gold medalist Jenny Thompson in calling for the EPO tests to
include sprinters as well as endurance athletes.
</P>
<P>
Talbot said he was concerned some cheats may escape at the
Sydney Games if drug testing officials ignored sprinters in the
EPO testing.
</P>
<P>
"There is talk going around that bothers me a little bit ...
that EPO only helps the distance people. It's just absolute
baloney," Talbot said.
</P>
<P>
"It's across the field. It's sprinters and everybody. With
sprinters, it changes the way they've got to work and they do less
and recover quicker. The distance people, of course, they've got a
greater capacity to work. (The drug testers) shouldn't just be
focussing on the distance people which they look like they're
doing right now," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has pledged between 300 and 700 EPO tests leading up
to and during the Games.
</P>
<P>
But reports Monday outlined how the test approved for Sydney
would only detect EPO use within 72 hours, rather than the one
developed by the Australian Sports Drug Laboratory which can
reveal usage within a month of an athlete taking it.
</P>
<P>
AOC president John Coates said the test was restricted to that
period to meet legal requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
