<HEADLINE> Olympic Torch Arrives in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Sydney, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic torch, which has
been touring Australia in the last three months, will be arriving
in Sydney, the Olympic host city later Monday.
</P>
<P>
City mayor Frank Sartor said the city is ready for the arrival
of the torch. "The city is ready and we are a great celebration
city. It will be a magical moment when the torch relay hits
central Sydney," he said.
</P>
<P>
The torch was originally lit in ancient Olympia and toured 14
Pacific island states before being brought to Australia June 8 at
Uluru (Ayers Rock) where hockey gold medallist Nova Peris Kneebone
became the first torch bearer.
</P>
<P>
Down Under, it was presented all over the country by ski,
sailing and steam boats, train and tram, solar car or simply on
foot.
</P>
<P>
It even went underwater at the Great Barrier Reef.
</P>
<P>
During the final days the torch will be at Botany Bay, where
captain James Cook landed in 1788 and on top of the Sydney Opera
House before it crosses Harbour Bridge.
</P>
<P>
While the final torch bearer will remain unknown until he or
she enters the Olympic stadium to light the cauldron for the 16-
day Games on Friday night, other famous people have already
carried it and will do so over the next days.
</P>
<P>
Swim world champion Samantha Riley will bring the torch to the
top of the opera house, golfer Greg Norman will run across Harbour
Bridge and swim legend Dawn Fraser carry it in downtown.
</P>
<P>
Others include Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli, actress Rachel
Ward,cricket captain Steve Waugh and tennis heroes John Newcombe
and Patrick Rafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
