<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to China Going Up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Statistics show that China has
absorbed a contractual foreign investment of 27.64 billion U.S.
dollars in the January-July period, an increase of 24.04 percent
over the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds used during that time amounted to 18.99 billion U.
S. dollars, with the decrease rate dropping from last year's two-
digit figure to the current one-digit figure.
</P>
<P>
Contracts involving 7.1 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
investment have been signed so far at the Fourth China Fair for
International Investment and Trade since it opened in the port
city of Xiamen on September 8.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the decrease of foreign investment in China
since the mid-1990s has been initially held back.
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Wu Yi said, "I'm very happy to see foreign
funds coming back."
</P>
<P>
Analysts pointed out, the economies in the countries and
regions which were affected by the Asian financial crisis are
recovering rapidly since the second half of last year. This has
resulted in an active effect on the inflow of foreign funds into
China, as two-thirds of the foreign investment in China have come
from 10 Asian countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the positive financial policy adopted by the
Chinese government, China's economy has increased by 8.1 percent
in the first half of the year, 0.6 percentage points higher than
that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China's economy has made a turn for the better
greatly increased the confidence level of foreign businesses to
invest in China, said Ma Xiuhong, assistant minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
