seven days in the Olympic Games, beginning with the lightest
division on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Spearheading the Japanese challenge is Shinichi Shinohara, who
won the men's open and heavyweight titles at the Worlds and will
face the toughest challenge from defending Olympic champion David
Douillet of France who missed the Worlds due to a back injury.
</P>
<P>
Women's four-time world bantamweight champion Ryoko Tamura is
also aiming to end her Olympic jinx after twice second places in
Barcelona and Atlanta, the only two losses in eight years for the
25-year-old Japanese.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta champion Tadahiro Nomura and world champion Manolo
Poulot of Cuba will battle for the men's bantamweight title, while
Kenzo Nakamura goes all out to defend his lightweight title
against such rivals as world champion James Pedro of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Other medal hopefuls include world champion Hidehiko Yoshida
and reigning world champion Kosei Inoue. 
