<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs Most Sought by Cheaters in Sport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Following is a list of main
drugs and performance-enhancing methods banned by the
International Olympic Committee:
</P>
<P>
Anabolic steroids:
</P>
<P>
Often used to boost muscles and to increase strength and power.
</P>
<P>
Side-effects for men include increased aggression, impotence
and kidney damage.
</P>
<P>
Side-effects for women include development of male features
with facial hair and deepening of the voice.
</P>
<P>
Erythropoletin (EPO):
</P>
<P>
A hormone produced by the kidneys to regulate the production of
red blood cells.
</P>
<P>
Synthetic EPO is misused by competitors to boost oxygen levels,
mostly in long-distance running, swimming and cycling.
</P>
<P>
Side-effects include the thickening the blood, death through
heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
The past 23 years recorded the deaths of some 30 cyclists.
</P>
<P>
Test to detect EPO will be used for the first time in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Blood Doping:
</P>
<P>
Some cheaters remove their own blood and re-injected shortly
before competition to increase oxygen capacity.
</P>
<P>
Useful for endurance and stamina-based sports.
</P>
<P>
Difficult to catch blood dopers, and the blood tests will not
be tested for in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Human growth hormone (HGH):
</P>
<P>
Growth hormone, produced by the pituitary gland to stimulate
the growth of bones, muscles and tissues, is used medically to
treat children whose own glands do not produce enough hormone to
allow normal growth.
</P>
<P>
Human growth hormone may be used to stimulate muscle and tissue
growth.
</P>
<P>
Side-effects include abnormal growth of the hands, feet, face
and internal organs.
</P>
<P>
Hard to detect. No test has been developed for it yet.
</P>
<P>
Stimulants:
</P>
<P>
Stimulants act on brain to increase alertness, decrease
feelings of fatigue and increase aggression.
</P>
<P>
Abuse can lead to increased blood pressure and body temperature,
increased and irregular heart beat and addiction.
</P>
<P>
Common stimulants include caffeine, cocaine and ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
Diuretics:
</P>
<P>
Often referred as masking agents, help to expel fluid from the
body.
</P>
<P>
Often used to increase the speed with which urine is produced
in order to make it more difficult to detect banned substances.
</P>
<P>
Frequently misused in sports with weight categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports May Deter Crime, Australian Study Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Sports activities may help
prevent crime, especially by young people and Aborigines in poor
or isolated areas, an Australian study tells the result.
</P>
<P>
The study report by the Australian Institute of Criminology (
AIC) said:"Crime prevention is not the primary objective of sport
and physical activity but it might be an extremely positive by-
product."
</P>
<P>
The report was based on a study of various international and
Australian sport projects, including wilderness therapy programmes
in the United States, ballet, judo and swimming in Canadian
housing projects, British football and sports carnivals in rural
Australia.
</P>
<P>
This found a link between sports involvement and crime levels.
</P>
<P>
AIC director Adam Graycar said sport provided a sense of
belonging, loyalty and support that young people, especially in
poor or isolated areas, were looking for.
</P>
<P>
"It provides opportunities for them to engage in behaviors
that are valued by society, diverting them from offending
behaviors," Graycar said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
