<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian men's soccer team
headcoach Jo Bonfrere said Monday that his team's Olympic gold
chance could be robbed by European clubs.
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman said those clubs had ignored FIFA directives
about releasing players for Olympic duty with English premier
league club Arsenal's Nwankwo Kanu the most notable absentee.
</P>
<P>
He said he had been kept waiting on players arriving late or
not at all and while uncertain about his starting line-up for
Nigeria's opener against Honduras on Wednesday, he was sure that
gold was not achievable.
</P>
<P>
"It is just not possible because of the pressure the clubs in
Europe are applying," he said. "It's impossible."
</P>
<P>
Bonfrere said the gifted Kanu was a huge loss and placed the
blame on Arsenal, which was reluctant to release him as an over-
age player, adding that the club had forced Kanu to sign a
contract which prevented him travelling to Australia for the Games.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old striker, who led his country to Olympic gold
in Atlanta four years ago, decided at the weekend to stay with the
London club rather than appear for his country.
</P>
<P>
"I love to play for my fatherland, my country, but I helped us
win the Olympic medal four years ago and because of my commitments
with my club, I decided it was not quite right to leave Arsenal
for so long and try to achieve something I had already achieved
before," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I spoke to the coach and the vice president and told them my
feelings. Now I just hope that when this is all over I can meet up
with the Nigerian national team again."
</P>
<P>
Bonfrere said another concern was over-age player Garba Lawal,
24, who plays with Dutch side Roda and will arrive in Australia
late.
</P>
<P>
"They forced him to play on Saturday, otherwise they would not
let him go. The club said it does not care about the FIFA rules,"
Bonfrere said, adding that Lawal should arrive late Monday, giving
him just 48 hours for the journey.
</P>
<P>
Under FIFA rules, nations competing in the Olympics can expect
players to arrive in camp up to six days before the start of
competition.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Honduras are in the same group as Australia and
Italy. 
</P>
