<HEADLINE> Stolen Olympic Flag Returned after 80 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- After 80 years, the stolen
original Olympic flag was returned to the International Olympic
Committee on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The flag was stolen by Hal Prieste at the 1920 Antwerp Olympic
Games where he won a diving bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Prieste, who climbed a 4.5-meter pole at the Antwerp Olympic
stadium for the flag, has kept it in a dusty suitcase in his New
Jersey home for eight decades.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the 103-year-old showman and jokester delivered the
flag from his wheelchair as the IOC opened its 111th Session in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
After arriving with his doctor, Prieste could not resist joking:
"Will there be a plaque with my name on it?"
</P>
<P>
He said later that he would not miss giving the flag away
because "I ain't gonna be around too long."
</P>
<P>
Carolyn Lamaina, the wife of Prieste's doctor, said he wanted
to take the flag to prove to people at home he was an Olympic
champion.
</P>
<P>
Once services in the U.S. Navy during World War I, the
California-born Prieste won the bronze in platform diving, and
went into show business after the Games as a dancer, tumbler and
pantomime artist.
</P>
<P>
His wife Hazel died 30 years ago without any children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
