<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Implements Radiation Protection Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Atomic Energy
Authority (AEA) has implemented a radiation protection program for
the benefit of the people, an official of the organization has
said.
</P>
<P>
Preenath Dias, chairman of the AEA, said that a special team of
officials had been engaged in carrying out regular inspection of
facilities where radioactive material and machines emitting
radiation are located and used in the country.
</P>
<P>
The authority has accorded highest priority to the measurement
of exposure levels of radiation among workers to ensure the levels
are less than internationally accepted limits.
</P>
<P>
At present the AEA issues about 140 licenses per year and about
1,000 workers are screened annually by the radiation protection
service.
</P>
<P>
The authority is also organizing training courses on radiation
protection to train workers who are being exposed to radiation, on
safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
The authority also provides consultation services on how to
construct buildings where radioactive materials and equipment are
located to protect the public from undue exposure to radiation.
</P>
<P>
Dais said that the main objective of the program was to
restrict the radiation exposure of workers who are engaged in
using nuclear technology for a number of useful activities and to
protect the public and the environment from radioactive
contamination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
