<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economy Grows 1.0 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy grew a real 1.0
percent in the April-June quarter from the previous term for the
second consecutive quarterly increase, the Economic Planning
Agency (EPA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter growth in gross domestic product (GDP)
translates into an annualized expansion of 4.2 percent, the agency
said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The domestic-demand component of GDP rose 1.0 percent, while
the external-demand component remained almost the same,the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Personal spending, which makes up about 60 percent of Japan's
GDP, rose 1.1 percent from the previous quarter, while corporate
capital spending fell 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Spending on home-care services was included in the personal-
spending category in the April-June quarter, following the
introduction of the public nursing-care insurance system in April.
</P>
<P>
Such spending increased overall personal spending by 0.2
percent, while increasing overall GDP by 0.1 percent, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment fell 0.8 percent following a 6.6 percent
increase in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the reporting quarter, Japan's GDP totaled 491,444.0
billion yen (4,633.6 billion dollars) in annualized terms,
compared with 486,401.7 billion yen (4,586.1 billion dollars) in
the previous period.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports grew by 3.9 percent while imports surged 4.9
percent during the three months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
