<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0430 GMT, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN -- German Transport Minister Reinhard Klimmt is still
unsatisfied with the latest output increase of the oil producing
countries, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
Klimmt was quoted by "Saarbrueker Zeitung" as saying that he
believed the 800,000 barrels per day increase decided by the
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
will give "certain relief" to soaring oil prices, but its members
"must truly produce more". (Germany-OPEC)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- In Ecuador, the U.S. dollar completely replaced the
country's 116-year-old currency, the sucre, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On January 9, former President Jamil Mahuad Witt proposed
adopting the U.S. dollar as the country's currency to stabilize
the foreign currency market, attract foreign investment and to
save the country from an economic crisis. Over the past year,
Ecuador has experienced Latin America's highest inflation rate at
90 percent. (Ecuador-Economy)
</P>
