<HEADLINE> Thousands Protest World Economic Forum Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Melbourne, a big city in
Australia, Monday witnessed the biggest demonstration in the past
decades when the World Economic Forum began its three-day Asia
Pacific Summit, a report from the city said.
</P>
<P>
According to a witness, the protesters are estimated at over 2,
000.
</P>
<P>
Police and protesters lined up against each other at all the
gates to the Crown Casino building where the summit is being held.
Traffic around the casino complex was being disrupted.
</P>
<P>
The protesters came from about 50 union, student and community
groups who opposed the globlization and see the World Economic
Forum as "a club of the world's richest 1,000 corporations."
</P>
<P>
At one entrance to the building, protesters scuffled with
police. Several protesters managed to get through the gates to the
complex but were stopped by the police, according to the report
from Melbourne. 
</P>
</TEXT>
