<HEADLINE> Mongolian Government Approves State Budget Amendments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A draft of amendments for
year 2000 state budget plans was approved by the new Mongolian
government on Monday and will be submitted to the State Great
Hural (parliament), the Ulan Bator Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government said the amendments reflect the
country's current economic and financial situation.
</P>
<P>
With the amendments, budget income will total 322 million U.S.
dollars, 7.6 million dollars more than the original budget's.
Expenditures will amount to 414 million dollars, 1.9 million
dollars less than the non-amended budget's.
</P>
<P>
Chultemiin Ulaan, minister of Finance and Economics, said that
budget income will be increased by mobilizing domestic reserves
and improving tax collection procedures. Savings will be made by
strengthening financial discipline and tightening spending.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party won the
parliamentary election on July 2, and the new government was
formed on August 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
