<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Steps up Fighting against Teenage Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Hungary will spend two
billion forint (7.55 million U.S. dollars) to fight teenage drug
abuse over the next two years, Deutsch Tamas, Hungarian Minister
Without Portfolio in Charge of Youth and Sports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to improve drug awareness education,
help teen addicts in recovery and to treat patients suffering from
drug abuse, said Deutsch Tamas.
</P>
<P>
Deutsch Tamas added over the next few years, all Hungarian
schools will hire people specifically to teach drug abuse
prevention.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, the central European country, has become a main drug-
trafficking channel, with more and more teen-agers hitting the
pipe each year. In Budapest, the number of 16 year-old drug
addicts has tripled since five years ago. Teenage drug abuse is
becoming one of Hungary's most agonizing social problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
