<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Economy Changes to the Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- In Ecuador, the U.S. dollar
completely replaced the country's 116-year-old currency, the sucre,
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On January 9, former President Jamil Mahuad Witt proposed
adopting the U.S. dollar as the country's currency to stabilize
the foreign currency market, attract foreign investment and to
save the country from an economic crisis. Over the past year,
Ecuador has experienced Latin America's highest inflation rate at
90 percent.
</P>
<P>
President Gustavo Noboa, who came to power on January 22 after
a coup, has adopted the policy and began the conversion process on
April 1, phasing in the circulation of the dollar with September 9
as the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Anyone with leftover sucre after it ceased circulation on
Sunday must exchange it for dollars in the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's sucre, named after a national hero who had led the
Ecuadorian people in a fight against Spanish colonialism, began
circulation on March 22, 1884.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
