<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Palestinian Declaration Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain said Sunday that it
welcomed a Palestinian decision to delay the declaration of
independent statehood until at least November 15.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome this confirmation from the Palestinians of their
renewed commitment to pursue negotiations and the search for peace,
" British Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain, who is responsible
for Middle East affairs, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides need to make every effort in the coming weeks," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hain's statement was issued shortly after the 129-member
Palestinian Central Council (PCC) said Sunday after a meeting in
Gaza that final preparations for statehood should be completed by
November 15.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian authority leader Yasser Arafat had earlier
repeatedly pledged to declare a state as early as next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Palestine and Israel failed to reach an agreement at a 15-
day summit initiated by U.S. President Bill Clinton at Camp David
in July.
</P>
<P>
Reports here quoted a senior Palestinian official as saying
that Arafat was expected to go to Egypt Monday to brief Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
