<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up
of China's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Coffin to Be Opened in Late September
</P>
<P>
A coffin in an ancient tomb dating back to some 2,000 years is
expected to be opened in Beijing by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists who have been excavating the tomb for eight
months will take the coffin out of the outer caskets and open it
in the Beijing Research Institute of Cultural Heritage in late
September.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, located 10 kilometers west from downtown Beijing, is
well preserved by a wooden structure, known as "ticou" in Chinese.
Ticou is a wooden tomb structure used during the Han dynasties (
206 B.C. to 220 A.D.). The wooden structure encased the tomb and
prevented moisture and earth entering the tomb.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Chinese Emperor Buried in Luxury
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have found more than 5,000 graves and
over 260 pits near the tomb of Jing, the fourth emperor of the
Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.) and his empress in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
These graves and pits, covering 3.5 square kilometers in area,
were found in good order and are divided into different groups
according to the identity of the buried people.
</P>
<P>
The graves and pits were constructed in the period between the
early Western Han and the mid Eastern Han Dynasty (25-220), said
Jiao Nanfeng, who led a group of archaeologists to unearth the
tomb of Emperor Jing.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Steles Discovered on Great Wall
</P>
<P>
Fourteen pieces of 400-year-old steles were discovered recently
on a section of the Great Wall near Shimenzhai Village, Funing
county in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
These steles are located along a four kilometer length of the
Great Wall, which lies on Mount Qingshi at an altitude of 600
meters.
</P>
<P>
The steles are almost free from artificial damage thanks to the
steepness of the area. The legible epigraphs record the
construction history of that section of the Great Wall built
between 1607 to 1608 in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
-- Public Fete of Chinese Ancestor Staged in Tianshui
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people from home and abroad gathered in Tianshui,
northwest China's Gansu Province, attending a ceremonious fete for
Fuxi, known as one of the first legendary ancestors of the Chinese
Nation.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held in front of the Fuxi Temple, the biggest
temple for commemorating the ancestor in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Museum of Silk Road Schemed in Xinjiang
</P>
<P>
China will turn the existing museum in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region into a technologically advanced one, showing
treasures found on the ancient Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
The country will pour 110 million yuan (about 13.3 million U.S.
dollars into the renovation project, which is scheduled to be
completed in 2005.
</P>
<P>
During the first phase of construction, a square, a fountain
and a garden surrounding the museum will be built, covering a
total of 9,200 square meters.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing Renovates Catholic Church
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital of Beijing has recently finished renovating
a Catholic church in the downtown commercial center of Wangfujing.
</P>
<P>
The St. Jausse Church, also named "Eastern Church" built in
1655 and occupying an area of 2,387 square meters, is the second
oldest Catholic church in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The local government started the renovation in May, and besides
the church itself, it also built a front square with a scope of 1.
2 hectares. Trees and grass were planted and various lighting
facilities were installed to show off the gorgeous building at
night.
</P>
<P>
-- Scholar Proves Marco Polo's Visit China
</P>
<P>
A professor with the Beijing University has claimed to have
found new evidence proving that Marco Polo (1254-1324), an Italian
traveler, did come to China.
</P>
<P>
Dang Baohai, a history professor, cited three examples from the
travel note taken by Marco Polo: a legend about the birth of a
Khan of Ouigour, an ancient nationality in northwest China;
Mongolian authorities forced to pull down ramparts built by Han
Nationality during the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368); and Kublai Khan
ordered to plant trees along roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
