<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0020 GMT, September 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African government on Sunday released
quotes from a Time magazine interview with President Thabo Mbeki
in an effort to quell the escalating controversy over the
president's views on HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has been strongly criticized for the government's AIDS
policies and for his support of AIDS theorists considered to be
dissident by mainstream science.  (S. Africa-AIDS)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- A young race official died on Sunday at the Italian
Grand Prix held in the Italian northern city of Monza. He was hit
by a wheel which flew into the air during a multi-car crash at the
start of the race.
</P>
<P>
The man, Paolo Gislimberti, 33, was given a heart massage
before being taken by ambulance to Monza hospital.  (Race-Killing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said on Sunday that one of its soldiers died
and another was seriously injured when British troops attacked a
rebel base in Sierra Leone to free six British soldiers held
hostage.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Defense is able to confirm that one U.K. (
United Kingdom) serviceman was killed in action during this
operation," the defense ministry said in a statement.  (Britain-
Sierra Leone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair agrees with a
European Union (EU) report that sanctions against Austria should
be lifted, a spokesman for Blair said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We agree with the report that the measures should be lifted,"
the spokesman said, but adding that Britain was not taking action
unilaterally to lift sanctions. (Britan-Austria-Sanction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Berlin -- German Transport Minister Reinhard Klimmt is still
unsatisfied with the latest output increase of the oil producing
countries, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
Klimmt was quoted by "Saarbrueker Zeitung" as saying that he
believed the 800,000 barrels per day increase decided by the
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
will give "certain relief" to soaring oil prices, but its members
"must truly produce more".  (Germany-OPEC) 
</P>
