<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottey Threatens to Walk out Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Fighting the IAAF to overturn
a drug test to earn her right to run in a sixth Olympic Games,
Merlene Ottey threatened on Sunday to boycott the Millennium
Olympics should she not be selected for the individual 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
Ottey, 40, was the superveteran in the women's sprinting world
with seven Olympic medals but a gold, finished fourth in the
Jamaican championships, and was only eligible for the 4x100m relay
as top three finishers of Peta Gaye-Dowdie, Beverley McDonald and
Tanya Lawrence were selected for the individual places.
</P>
<P>
Ottey said that she would give up that place if the Jamaican
Federation did not select her for the individual event, saying
that "I think I will go on vacation."
</P>
<P>
After convincing an IAAF arbitration panel that a positive drug
test for nandrolone was flawed, Ottey has returned to something
like her old form, running 10.99 and 11.00 seconds. She ran a wind-
assisted 10.91 and a legal 11.15 on the Gold Coast yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"My goal for this year was to run a personal best. It might be
good enough to get a medal, we will see," said Ottey.
</P>
<P>
She said her record during 20 years should earn her some
consideration as she has won 14 world championships and seven
Olympic medals.
</P>
<P>
"It was fourth in my trials, but they have helped other
athletes in the past," she said.
</P>
<P>
"That was the first time in 20 years of running for Jamaica
that I have finished outside the top three. They have made rules
for other athletes to prove their fitness in the past, so why
should I be treated differently?"
</P>
<P>
"I think I have proved my fitness. I am just looking for one
spot in the 100, this is what I told them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
