<HEADLINE> Roundup: Increased Bicommunal Contacts Auspicious for Divided Cyprus by Liu Xingchang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Contacts between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots in divided Cyprus have increased noticeably in
recent months as leaders of the sides are engaged in proximity
talks for possible reunification.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that bicommunal meetings have quadrupled since
September last year thanks to the uplift of political atmosphere in
the island country, which has been divided into Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and seized the
northern third of the island following a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots in 1983 proclaimed a breakaway republic, which
is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the island by a
bicommunal, bizonal federation formula. But Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash, angered by the European Union's (EU) decision to
deny Turkey a EU candidacy, walked out of peace talks with Cypriot
government and banned almost all the bicommunal contacts.
</P>
<P>
The devastating earthquakes that hit Turkey in August and Greece
in September last year brought out detente in the two countries'
relationship. The two countries have offered aid and condolences to
each other and the "earthquake diplomacy" finally led to Greece's
drop of opposition to Ankara's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-brokered proximity talks between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots have been conducted since last December, and the
fourth round will start in New York Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the contacts occurred in events arranged with the help
of the U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) in the buffer
zone, involving individuals, groups and political parties.
</P>
<P>
A rapprochement fair at Pergamos park in the eastern part of the
island was organized by Greek Cypriot left-wing AKEL party and
Turkish Cypriot Patriotic Unity Movement earlier this year,
attracting 2,000 participants from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Party leaders of both sides also met several times this year to
exchange views on the developments of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The bicommunal activities are widely welcomed on the island,
although there are so far different views about the contacts. Some
groups and political parties believe that these contacts help build
up trust between the sides.
</P>
<P>
AKEL, active in the contacts, has expressed that although the
rapprochement efforts in themselves could not solve the Cyprus
issue, they could create a positive climate between the communities
to ensure the viability of a solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Urges Members to Join Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) Monday urged its members to join the
free trade area (FTA) to be launched at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The launching of the FTA on October 31 and the establishment
of a single market of about 350 million people will add the voice
of an integrated region to international economics and politics,
said COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha while opening the
sixth meeting of the COMESA's Trade and Customs Committee here
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
"We should, therefore, put in place support programs and
arrangements for the smooth functioning of the free trade area,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
At the fifth summit of the COMESA Authority held in Mauritius
this May, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi,
Mauritius, Sudan, Uganda Zambia and Zimbabwe undertook to remove
all their remaining tariffs between each other by 31 October to
usher in a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Since the Mauritius meeting, Seychelles has confirmed that it
will join the FTA in June next year while Rwanda and Burundi are
making good progress to join the FTA, Mwencha said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to decide on the derogation of Swaziland and Namibia.
We hope that Ethiopia, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and
the Comoros will join the FTA when circumstances permit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Because not all member states have undertaken to implement the
COMESA FTA on October 31, 2000, this will pose a question as how
FTA members will conduct their trade with non-FTA members, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha also tried to allay fears that the removal of tariffs
between FTA members may cause significant loss to government
revenues.
</P>
<P>
The revenues that the governments will give up as a result of
the FTA is very small and will be easily compensated for through
improved tax administration and levying of domestic sales tax such
as value added tax on the resulting larger volume of imports, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Since the FTA is one of the stages leading towards a common
market and eventually an African economic community, a formula
should be worked out on the relationship governing trade between
COMESA FTA member states and COMESA non-FTA member states, Mwencha
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks to Move to Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A meeting to find lasting
peace in troubled Burundi will be held in Kenya's capital Nairobi
on September 20, the Nation newspaper reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to thrash out modalities for a
ceasefire, the formation of a transitional government bringing all
political parties on board and the integration of Hutus into the
Tutsi-dominated army.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi talks is a follow-up of the Arusha meeting in
Tanzania, where the warring parties in Burundi signed a peace
accord on August 28 at a ceremony witnessed by U.S. President Bill
Clinton on the invitation of Nelson Mandela, mediator of Burundi
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will be in Nairobi for the September 20 peace talks and
Uganda President Yoweri Museveni has confirmed his participation.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan President Paul Kagame, Burundi President Pierre Buyoya,
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa and representatives of
political parties in dispute are also expected to attend the
meeting, while France and Belgium will be represented by officials
from their embassies in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Foreign Affairs Ministry is currently doing
preparations for the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
