<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Studies to Raise Oil Production to 100,000 BPD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Mexico studies to raise
from 50,000 to 100,000 barrels a day (bpd) its supply of oil in
the last quarter of the year, after the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) is raising its output by 800,000
barrels a day, official sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, which is not an OPEC member, has advocated in recent
years a production policy that will permit to maintain the balance
of the international market prices to prevent economic crises of
world consequences.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Energy Ministry's sources explained Monday that they
will wait for the international market reaction to the OPEC
decision, to calculate the crude for export volume to be adopted
by the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the same sources, Mexico will have an additional
producing capability of up to 200,000 barrels of oil a day, which
will permit it to take a decision on the expansion of its exports
in the following weeks.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the increase will be much smaller despite
this surplus, and that their estimations point to an increase of
50,000 to 100,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
The same sources noted that other oil producing countries could
take advantage of the OPEC decision to approve an increase in
their output.
</P>
<P>
The extra output would take Mexico's nominal export base to
over 1.8 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is currently produces 3 million bpd of oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
