<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Refuses to Pull Out of Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Monday refused to
bow to pressure to pull out of Sierra Leone after a dramatic
weekend raid to free British soldiers taken hostage by rebel
groups in that western African nation, saying it could even send
in reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon said no decisions had yet been
made on troop requirements in the war-ravaged former British
colony. But he added that troop numbers could be bolstered if a
threat of revenge attacks by militia there emerged.
</P>
<P>
"We constantly review our involvement in what is clearly a
dangerous environment like Sierra Leone," Hoon told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly if that is the judgment that is reached, then the
safety and security of British forces in Sierra Leone is
absolutely paramount," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel militia in Sierra Leone seized 11 British soldiers on
August 25 and later freed five of them before Britain attacked
their base on Sunday morning and freed all the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The captivated British soldiers were members of a unit training
a new Sierra Leone army following a 1999 peace deal to end a civil
war which has rumbled on since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Britain's opposition Conservative party blasted the government'
s role in Sierra Leone as an "ethical mess", calling for "a
serious rethink" about military commitments there.
</P>
<P>
British newspapers also urged a fresh look at army involvement
overseas in the wake of Sunday's raid -- although the nation's
press was quick to highlight how successful Sunday's operation had
been.  
</P>
</TEXT>
