<HEADLINE> Albright Welcomes Palestinian Move to Postpone Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Monday welcomed a decision by the
Palestinian Central Council to postpone a declaration of statehood
for two months.
</P>
<P>
"This decision reflects a Palestinian commitment to the peace
process and their commitment to continue negotiations," Albright
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The 129-member Central Council of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization, backing down from a pledge to declare statehood no
later than September 13, decided to postpone the declaration of
statehood for two months at a meeting held in Gaza on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the Palestinian move will give Washington
more time to work on a settlement between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to continue doing what we are doing. There are
various combinations of meetings that can take place and there are
lots of things that we will be looking at," she said.
</P>
<P>
But she noted that "there is still obviously a difficult road
ahead and we are going to be looking to the parties to make the
tough decisions that will lead to a lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to continue to be of assistance as meetings go
forward," she added. 
</P>
