<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes Entertainment Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Monday criticized the entertainment industry for marketing
violent movies, music and video games to children.
</P>
<P>
"They're trying to sell their movies and other products to the
very people that they themselves say shouldn't see them," Clinton
said in an address to the Jewish Community Center in Scarsdale,
New York state.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed his support for a government report
criticizing the entertainment industry's market tactics and urged
Hollywood to stop targeting children with their restricted violent
products only for adults.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was released here Monday by the Federal Trade
Commission, accused the entertainment industry of aggressively
marketing violent content to children, undermining the ratings
system used by the entertainment industry to warn against the
violent contents.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that 80 percent of the movies, half of the
video games and one-quarter of the CDs are being marketed
intentionally to the very children who are prohibited from buying
them.
</P>
<P>
U.S. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who appeared together
with President Clinton, joined her husband in calling on Hollywood
to stop its marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
She said that if elected to the U.S. Senate from New York, she
would work to implement a voluntary, uniform ratings system for
all entertainment media.
</P>
<P>
"Today, I'm calling on the industry to immediately stop
marketing adult and violent entertainment to children and
voluntarily restrict the way they advertise and market it so that
we no longer find it during prime time family hours or inside the
magazines read mostly by our kids," she said.
</P>
<P>
"It's the right thing to do, it should be done, and I hope that
the industry will act," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
