<HEADLINE> Blair Promises Billion Pound Plan for E-Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair promised on Monday to pump one billion pounds into
delivering all government services via the Internet by 2005,
saying Britain was catching up in the global race to get online.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a high-tech business park in the English Midlands,
Blair also pledged money to help small businesses link up to the
net and said the government would soon open the first of 6,000
Internet centers in poor communities.
</P>
<P>
He promised that Britain will become the best country in the
world for e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also announced the first raft of 600 online
centers to give hi-tech access to poorer communities.
</P>
<P>
Blair said the government's initiative, called UK Online, was
aimed at ensuring the country's economy did not fall into two -
old and new.
</P>
<P>
"There is no new economy. There is one economy, all of it being
transformed by information technology," he said. "What is
happening is no dot.com fad that will come and go - it is a
profound economic revolution."
</P>
<P>
The economy was all one and what mattered was whether companies
mastered the information technology change, he told his audience
in Loughborough, central England.
</P>
<P>
The government drive had three aims: to make sure the UK was
the best place to do e-commerce, to ensure universal net access
for all and to ensure all government services were available on
the net, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The one billion pound (1.42 billion U.S. dollar) package, from
funds already allocated in Chancellor Gordon Brown's July spending
review, aims to ensure that by 2005 Britons should be able to fill
in tax forms and apply for driving licenses and new passports on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
By 2002, all companies bidding for government contracts will
have to submit their bids electronically, Blair added.
</P>
<P>
He also announced an additional 15 million pounds to provide
help and advice to companies wanting to exploit new technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
