<HEADLINE> Belgian Government Rules Out Fuel Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Prime Minister Guy
Verhofstadt said Monday that a cut in excise tax on fuel oil was
not the right way to solve the problem of rising prices.
</P>
<P>
Belga New Agency, Belgium's national news agency, said the
prime minister was speaking in New York during a trade promotion
tour.
</P>
<P>
Belgian truckers demanding tax cuts to drive down the oil price
brought Brussels the capital to a chaos Monday, the second day of
protests by transport workers. Truck drivers vowed to continue
their blockade after storming from a meeting with Transport
Minister Isabelle Durant.
</P>
<P>
The news agency did not say what was the prime minister's
alternative to combat rising oil prices, but quoted him as saying
that the issue should be discussed at Friday's cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian protest was launched just as a six-day blockade of
French oil refineries and storage depots came to an end but
protests gathered pace in Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, truckers, taxi drivers, farmers, tour
operators and others who claim that high oil prices are hurting
their businesses, continue their protests in France, the
Netherlands and Germany.
</P>
<P>
In France, protesters cleared blockades only after the
government made concessions to them. However, protests continued
in scattered French cities, despite government concessions.
</P>
<P>
A wave of protests has moved across Europe after truckers and
farming groups in France won a 15 percent cut in fuel tax
following their blockades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
