<HEADLINE> Thousands of British Filling Stations Run Dry Amid Nation-wide Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of filling stations
in Britain have run out of key grades of petrol and diesel amid
nationwide blockades at refineries, terminals and depots and panic
buying by motorists, oil firms said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Esso, Britain's leading petrol retailer, said over 300 of its 1,
600 sites had run out of petrol and diesel.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco, Britain's second largest retailer, said that 40
percent of its petrol stations nationwide, or 600 out of 1,500
sites, had run out of products - mostly premium unleaded and
diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
Over one-third of petrol stations run by Texaco, another fuel
company in Britain, have also run dry or are very close to doing
so.
</P>
<P>
But the British government vowed to stand its ground on Monday
in the face of the mounting protests against high fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair, anxious to avoid a repeat of chaos
in France which led to a government climbdown, told a business
meeting in Loughborough, central England, that protesters were
misdirecting their anger.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot and we will not alter government policy on petrol
through blockades and pickets. That is not the way to make policy
in Britain," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of over 13,000 petrol retail sites in Britain,
according to the Institute of Petroleum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
