<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronaut, Cosmonaut Take Successful Spacewalk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. astronaut and a
Russian cosmonaut on Monday drifted out of space shuttle Atlantis,
making a successful climb up the international space station, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The mission, designed to lay cable and install a boom for a
navigation unit on the exterior of the 42-meter station, lasted 6
hours and 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Carrying the bundled cables on their backs along with the boom
and their tools, Edward Lu of the United States and Yuri
Malenchenko of Russia ventured an astounding 33 meters from
Atlantis' cargo bay, where the space station had been anchored for
the past day.
</P>
<P>
It was the farthest distance an NASA spacewalker had ventured
while tethered.
</P>
<P>
The spacewalk official inside Mission Control, Mike Hess,
likened the foray to working on the 11th story of a 13-story
building -- with a much better view, 370 kilometers above earth.
</P>
<P>
To get to the top of the towering station, Lu and Malenchenko
first took a 12 meter ride on the shuttle robot arm. Then they
ascended hand over hand like rock climbers, clipping and
unclipping their tethers like climbing ropes as they moved up.
</P>
<P>
The work went flawlessly, ending 16 minutes ahead of schedule
even with an additional brief task.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis, launched from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida
last Friday, linked up with the station as the spacecraft soared
above Kazakhstan on Sunday after a two-day chase.
</P>
<P>
Astronauts and cosmonauts of the space shuttle will enter the
station Tuesday to haul in thousands of pounds of supplies for the
first residents of the complex, due in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Pledges to Investigate Flood Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Giuliano
Amato pledged Monday that the culprits of the flood that killed 12
people when it swept through a Calabrian campsite early Sunday
will be brought to book.
</P>
<P>
A statement released after a cabinet meeting voiced "deep
condolences" on his own and the government's behalf and gave
assurances that the "responsibilities for the disaster will be
identified."
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also declared a state of natural calamity in the
region of Calabria, where other mostly eastern areas were
devastated by torrential rain that started beating down on
Thursday after six months of almost complete drought.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency, which will go into effect early
tomorrow, was matched by special funds totaling 30 billion lire (
about 13.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twelve people were killed on the Sunday's flash flood in
Soverato, south town of region Calabria, and at least four others
were missing.
</P>
<P>
Various investigations have been opened into the disaster, by
the judiciary and the regional and city governments, to start with,
and a suit has been filed by the WWF for manslaughter and civil
damages.
</P>
<P>
One of the main mysteries is why a campsite should be
authorized with 45 percent of its area within the river bed, or
for that matter a car dealership's parking area almost fully
inside it.
</P>
<P>
Confirming that investigators have already confiscated official
documents at Soverato's town hall, the prosecutor's office said
that the charges currently being considered are multiple
manslaughter in causing a flood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
