<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended
lower for the second consecutive session Monday as investors
worried about the corporate earnings in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 25.16 at 11,195.49
points. The blue chip index fell 39.22 points last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 82.06 at 3,896.35 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 5.24 at 1,489.26.
</P>
<P>
Stocks fell after a Goldman Sachs analyst cut IBM's earnings
expectations in the third quarter. In the previous sessions, a
number of companies warned that their earnings in the third
quarter would not meet expectations. Among them were DuPont,
Campbell Soup, First Data and MPower Communications.
</P>
<P>
The fresh warning today added to traders' worries about
investment returns in the slowing U.S. economy, dragging down high-
tech companies such as Oracle, Sun Microsystems and Cisco Systems
as well as IBM.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times in the
past 15 months in an effort to cool off the economy and keep
inflation at bay. Higher rates could increase costs and lower
profits for companies.
</P>
<P>
A surge in some energy and financial services stocks did not
stop the market's falling today. Shares of Goldman Sachs rose
after the investment bank announced that it had agreed to buy the
Wall Street market maker firm Spear Leeds &AMP; Kellogg for 6.5
billion U.S. dollars in stock and cash to expand its customer base.
Shares of J.P. Morgan was also up.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 1.51 at 677.24 and the American Stock
Exchange index was up 1.58 at 969.50. But the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies was down 2.08 at 533.26.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,541 up, 1,303 down and 531
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 895.71 million shares from 958.65
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000911.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Launches Campaign in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush Monday launched campaign in
Florida, a state he took it for granted that he would win a few
months ago as his younger brother Jeb Bush was governor.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to carry Florida," Bush told a campaign rally in the
state with 25 electoral votes and a large population of seniors.
</P>
<P>
Texas Governor Bush held an edge over Gore in Florida before
the two parties' conventions in August, but new private polls
conducted by both parties show the race even or Vice President Al
Gore leads now.
</P>
<P>
Bush launched his campaign in Florida with a new slogan "Real
Plans for Real People" and a fresh style, talking informally with
elderly voters and answering questions for more than 30 minutes at
a local community center.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who is spending several hundred thousand dollars for
Florida TV ads, briefly talked about his 198 billion dollars plan
to overhaul the health care system for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The governor also met privately with several seniors who would
benefit from his plan to provide 48 billion dollars in
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
His spokeswoman Karen Hughes said that Bush would travel this
week from Florida to Missouri, Washington State, California, New
Mexico and back to Austin, Texas on Friday, visiting nine cities
en route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
